[src:dsp/aliasing] The velocity of the camera, moving towards the right, constantly increases at the same rate (while to the camera, the objects appear sliding to the left).
[src:dsp/aliasing] Halfway through the 24-second loop, the objects appear to suddenly shift and head in the reverse direction, towards the right.
[src:dsp/aliasing] In digital signal processing, **aliasing** is a phenomenon in which a reconstructed signal from samples of the original signal contains low frequency components that are not present in the original one.
[src:dsp/aliasing] This is caused when, in the original signal, there are components at frequency exceeding a certain frequency called Nyquist frequency, ${\textstyle f_{s}/2}$ , where ${\textstyle f_{s}}$ is the sampling frequency (undersampling).
[src:dsp/aliasing] This is because typical reconstruction methods use low frequency components while there are a number of frequency components, called aliases, which sampling result in the identical sample.
[src:dsp/aliasing] It also often refers to the distortion or artifact that results when a signal reconstructed from samples is different from the original continuous signal.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Aliasing can occur in signals sampled in time, for instance in digital audio or the stroboscopic effect, and is referred to as **temporal aliasing**.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Aliasing in spatially sampled signals (e.g., moiré patterns in digital images) is referred to as **spatial aliasing**.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Aliasing is generally avoided by applying low-pass filters or anti-aliasing filters (AAF) to the input signal before sampling and when converting a signal from a higher to a lower sampling rate.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Suitable reconstruction filtering should then be used when restoring the sampled signal to the continuous domain or converting a signal from a lower to a higher sampling rate.
[src:dsp/aliasing] For spatial anti-aliasing, the types of anti-aliasing include fast approximate anti-aliasing (FXAA), multisample anti-aliasing (MSAA), and supersampling.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Temporal anti-aliasing is a special case of MSAA where pixel samples are collected over multiple frames.
[src:dsp/aliasing] When a digital image is viewed, a reconstruction is performed by a display or printer device.
[src:dsp/aliasing] If the image data is processed incorrectly during sampling or reconstruction, the reconstructed image will differ from the original image, and an alias is seen.
[src:dsp/aliasing] An example of spatial aliasing is the moiré pattern observed in a poorly pixelized image of a brick wall.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Spatial anti-aliasing techniques avoid such poor pixelizations.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Temporal aliasing is a major concern in the sampling of video and audio signals.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Music, for instance, may contain high-frequency components that are outside human's hearing range and hence inaudible.
[src:dsp/aliasing] If a piece of music is sampled at 32,000 samples per second (Hz), any frequency components at or above 16,000 Hz (the Nyquist frequency for this sampling rate) will cause aliasing when the music is reproduced by a digital-to-analog converter (DAC).
[src:dsp/aliasing] The high frequencies in the analog signal will appear as lower frequencies (wrong alias) in the recorded digital sample and, hence, cannot be reproduced by the DAC.
[src:dsp/aliasing] To prevent this, an anti-aliasing filter is used to remove components above the Nyquist frequency prior to sampling.
[src:dsp/aliasing] In video or cinematography, temporal aliasing results from the limited frame rate, and causes the wagon-wheel effect, whereby a spoked wheel appears to rotate too slowly or even backwards.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Aliasing has changed its apparent frequency of rotation.
[src:dsp/aliasing] A reversal of direction can be described as a negative frequency.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Temporal aliasing frequencies in video and cinematography are determined by the frame rate of the camera, but the relative intensity of the aliased frequencies is determined by the shutter timing (exposure time) or the use of a temporal aliasing reduction filter during filming.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Like the video camera, most sampling schemes are periodic; that is, they have a characteristic sampling frequency in time or in space.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Digital cameras provide a certain number of samples (pixels) per degree or per radian, or samples per mm in the focal plane of the camera.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Audio signals are sampled (digitized) with an analog-to-digital converter, which produces a constant number of samples per second.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Some of the most dramatic and subtle examples of aliasing occur when the signal being sampled also has periodic content.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Actual signals have a finite duration and their frequency content, as defined by the Fourier transform, has no upper bound.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Some amount of aliasing always occurs when such continuous functions over time are sampled.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Functions whose frequency content is bounded (*bandlimited*) have an infinite duration in the time domain.
[src:dsp/aliasing] If sampled at a high enough rate, determined by the *bandwidth*, the original function can, in theory, be perfectly reconstructed from the infinite set of samples.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Sometimes aliasing is used intentionally on signals with no low-frequency content, called *bandpass* signals.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Undersampling, which creates low-frequency aliases, can produce the same result, with less effort, as frequency-shifting the signal to lower frequencies before sampling at the lower rate.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Some digital channelizers exploit aliasing in this way for computational efficiency.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Sinusoids are an important type of periodic function, because realistic signals are often modeled as the summation of many sinusoids of different frequencies and different amplitudes (for example, with a Fourier series or transform).
[src:dsp/aliasing] Understanding what aliasing does to the individual sinusoids is useful in understanding what happens to their sum.
[src:dsp/aliasing] A frequency spectrum of the samples produces equally strong responses at all those frequencies.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Without collateral information, the frequency of the original function is ambiguous.
[src:dsp/aliasing] So, the functions and their frequencies are said to be *aliases* of each other.
[src:dsp/aliasing] thus, we can write all the alias frequencies as positive values: $f_{_{N}}(f)\triangleq \left|f+Nf_{\rm {s}}\right|$ .
[src:dsp/aliasing] For example, a snapshot of the lower right frame of Fig.2 shows a component at the actual frequency f and another component at alias $f_{_{-1}}(f)$ .
[src:dsp/aliasing] As f increases during the animation, $f_{_{-1}}(f)$ decreases.
[src:dsp/aliasing] The point at which they are equal $(f=f_{s}/2)$ is an axis of symmetry called the ***folding frequency***, also known as ***Nyquist frequency***.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Aliasing matters when one attempts to reconstruct the original waveform from its samples.
[src:dsp/aliasing] The most common reconstruction technique produces the smallest of the $f_{_{N}}(f)$ frequencies.
[src:dsp/aliasing] So, it is usually important that $f_{0}(f)$ be the unique minimum.
[src:dsp/aliasing] A necessary and sufficient condition for that is $f_{s}/2>|f|,$ called the ***Nyquist condition***.
[src:dsp/aliasing] The lower left frame of Fig.2 depicts the typical reconstruction result of the available samples.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Until f exceeds the Nyquist frequency, the reconstruction matches the actual waveform (upper left frame).
[src:dsp/aliasing] After that, it is the low frequency alias of the upper frame.
[src:dsp/aliasing] The figures below offer additional depictions of aliasing, due to sampling.
[src:dsp/aliasing] A graph of amplitude vs frequency (not time) for a single sinusoid at frequency 0.6 *f*s and some of its aliases at 0.4 *f*s, 1.4 *f*s, and 1.6 *f*s would look like the 4 black dots in Fig.3.
[src:dsp/aliasing] The red lines depict the paths (loci) of the 4 dots if we were to adjust the frequency and amplitude of the sinusoid along the solid red segment (between *f*s/2 and *f*s).
[src:dsp/aliasing] No matter what function we choose to change the amplitude vs frequency, the graph will exhibit symmetry between 0 and *f*s.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Folding is often observed in practice when viewing the frequency spectrum of real-valued samples, such as Fig.4.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Complex sinusoids are waveforms whose samples are complex numbers ( ${\textstyle z=Ae^{i\theta }=A(\cos \theta +i\sin \theta )}$ ), and the concept of negative frequency is necessary to distinguish them.
[src:dsp/aliasing] In that case, the frequencies of the aliases are given by just: *f*N(*f*) = *f* + *N f*s.
[src:dsp/aliasing] (In real sinusoids, as shown in the above, all alias frequencies can be written as positive frequencies $f_{_{N}}(f)\triangleq \left|f+Nf_{\rm {s}}\right|$ because of sine functions as odd functions.) Therefore, as f increases from 0 to *f*s, *f*−1(*f*) also increases (from –*f*s to 0).
[src:dsp/aliasing] Consequently, complex sinusoids do not exhibit *folding*.
[src:dsp/aliasing] When the condition *f*s/2 > *f* is met for the highest frequency component of the original signal, then it is met for all the frequency components, a condition called the Nyquist criterion.
[src:dsp/aliasing] That is typically approximated by filtering the original signal to attenuate high frequency components before it is sampled.
[src:dsp/aliasing] These attenuated high frequency components still generate low-frequency aliases, but typically at low enough amplitudes that they do not cause problems.
[src:dsp/aliasing] A filter chosen in anticipation of a certain sample frequency is called an anti-aliasing filter.
[src:dsp/aliasing] The filtered signal can subsequently be reconstructed, by interpolation algorithms, without significant additional distortion.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Most sampled signals are not simply stored and reconstructed.
[src:dsp/aliasing] But the fidelity of a theoretical reconstruction (via the Whittaker–Shannon interpolation formula) is a customary measure of the effectiveness of sampling.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Historically the term *aliasing* evolved from radio engineering because of the action of superheterodyne receivers.
[src:dsp/aliasing] If it is strong enough it can interfere with reception of the desired signal.
[src:dsp/aliasing] This unwanted signal is known as an *image* or *alias* of the desired signal.
[src:dsp/aliasing] The first written use of the terms "alias" and "aliasing" in signal processing appears to be in a 1949 unpublished Bell Laboratories technical memorandum by John Tukey and Richard Hamming.
[src:dsp/aliasing] That paper includes an example of frequency aliasing dating back to 1922.
[src:dsp/aliasing] The first *published* use of the term "aliasing" in this context is due to Blackman and Tukey in 1958.
[src:dsp/aliasing] In their preface to the Dover reprint of this paper, they point out that the idea of aliasing had been illustrated graphically by Stumpf ten years prior.
[src:dsp/aliasing] The 1949 Bell technical report refers to aliasing as though it is a well-known concept, but does not offer a source for the term.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Gwilym Jenkins and Maurice Priestley credit Tukey with introducing it in this context, though an analogous concept of aliasing had been introduced a few years earlier in fractional factorial designs.
[src:dsp/aliasing] While Tukey did significant work in factorial experiments and was certainly aware of aliasing in fractional designs, it cannot be determined whether his use of "aliasing" in signal processing was consciously inspired by such designs.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Aliasing occurs whenever the use of discrete elements to capture or produce a continuous signal causes frequency ambiguity.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Spatial aliasing, particular of angular frequency, can occur when reproducing a light field or sound field with discrete elements, as in 3D displays or wave field synthesis of sound.
[src:dsp/aliasing] The lack of parallax on viewer movement in 2D images and in 3-D film produced by stereoscopic glasses (in 3D films the effect is called "yawing", as the image appears to rotate on its axis) can similarly be seen as loss of angular resolution, all angular frequencies being aliased to 0 (constant).
[src:dsp/aliasing] The qualitative effects of aliasing can be heard in the following audio demonstration.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Six sawtooth waves are played in succession, with the first two sawtooths having a fundamental frequency of 440 Hz (A4), the second two having fundamental frequency of 880 Hz (A5), and the final two at 1760 Hz (A6).
[src:dsp/aliasing] The sawtooths alternate between bandlimited (non-aliased) sawtooths and aliased sawtooths and the sampling rate is 22050 Hz.
[src:dsp/aliasing] The bandlimited sawtooths are synthesized from the sawtooth waveform's Fourier series such that no harmonics above the Nyquist frequency (11025 Hz = 22050 Hz / 2 here) are present.
[src:dsp/aliasing] The aliasing distortion in the lower frequencies is increasingly obvious with higher fundamental frequencies, and while the bandlimited sawtooth is still clear at 1760 Hz, the aliased sawtooth is degraded and harsh with a buzzing audible at frequencies lower than the fundamental.
[src:dsp/aliasing] A form of spatial aliasing can also occur in antenna arrays or microphone arrays used to estimate the direction of arrival of a wave signal, as in geophysical exploration by seismic waves.
[src:dsp/aliasing] Waves must be sampled more densely than two points per wavelength, or the wave arrival direction becomes ambiguous.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] The term *convolution* refers to both the resulting function and to the process of computing it.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] The integral is evaluated for all values of shift, producing the convolution function.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] The choice of which function is reflected and shifted before the integral does not change the integral result (see commutativity).
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Graphically, it expresses how the 'shape' of one function is modified by the other.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] For complex-valued functions, the cross-correlation operator is the adjoint of the convolution operator.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Convolution has applications that include probability, statistics, acoustics, spectroscopy, signal processing and image processing, computer vision and human vision, geophysics, engineering, physics, and differential equations.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] The convolution can be defined for functions on Euclidean space and other groups (as algebraic structures).
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] For example, periodic functions, such as the discrete-time Fourier transform, can be defined on a circle and convolved by periodic convolution.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] (See row 18 at DTFT § Properties.) A *discrete convolution* can be defined for functions on the set of integers.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Generalizations of convolution have applications in the field of numerical analysis and numerical linear algebra, and in the design and implementation of finite impulse response filters in signal processing.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Computing the inverse of the convolution operation is known as deconvolution.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] The convolution of f {\displaystyle f} ({\displaystyle f}) and g {\displaystyle g} ({\displaystyle g}) is written f ∗ g {\displaystyle f*g} ({\displaystyle f*g}), denoting the operator with the symbol ∗ {\displaystyle *} ({\displaystyle *}).
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] It is defined as the integral of the product of the two functions after one is reflected about the y-axis and shifted.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] While the symbol t {\displaystyle t} ({\displaystyle t}) is used above, it need not represent the time domain.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] For the multi-dimensional formulation of convolution, see *domain of definition* (below).
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] which has to be interpreted carefully to avoid confusion.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] respectively, the convolution operation ( f ∗ g ) ( t ) {\displaystyle (f*g)(t)} ({\displaystyle (f*g)(t)}) can be defined as the inverse Laplace transform of the product of F ( s ) {\displaystyle F(s)} ({\displaystyle F(s)}) and G ( s ) {\displaystyle G(s)} ({\displaystyle G(s)}).
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Note that F ( s ) ⋅ G ( s ) {\displaystyle F(s)\cdot G(s)} ({\displaystyle F(s)\cdot G(s)}) is the bilateral Laplace transform of ( f ∗ g ) ( t ) {\displaystyle (f*g)(t)} ({\displaystyle (f*g)(t)}).
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] A similar derivation can be done using the unilateral Laplace transform (one-sided Laplace transform).
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] The convolution operation also describes the output (in terms of the input) of an important class of operations known as *linear time-invariant* (LTI).
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] See LTI system theory for a derivation of convolution as the result of LTI constraints.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] In terms of the Fourier transforms of the input and output of an LTI operation, no new frequency components are created.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] The existing ones are only modified (amplitude and/or phase).
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] In other words, the output transform is the pointwise product of the input transform with a third transform (known as a transfer function).
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] See Convolution theorem for a derivation of that property of convolution.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Conversely, convolution can be derived as the inverse Fourier transform of the pointwise product of two Fourier transforms.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] One of the earliest uses of the convolution integral appeared in D'Alembert's derivation of Taylor's theorem in *Recherches sur différents points importants du système du monde,* published in 1754.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] is used by Sylvestre François Lacroix on page 505 of his book entitled *Treatise on differences and series*, which is the last of 3 volumes of the encyclopedic series: *Traité du calcul différentiel et du calcul intégral*, Chez Courcier, Paris, 1797–1800.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Soon thereafter, convolution operations appear in the works of Pierre Simon Laplace, Jean-Baptiste Joseph Fourier, Siméon Denis Poisson, and others.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] The term itself did not come into wide use until the 1950s or 1960s.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Prior to that it was sometimes known as *Faltung* (which means *folding* in German), *composition product*, *superposition integral*, and *Carson's integral*.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Yet it appears as early as 1903, though the definition is rather unfamiliar in older uses.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] is a particular case of composition products considered by the Italian mathematician Vito Volterra in 1913.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] where t 0 {\displaystyle t_{0}} ({\displaystyle t_{0}}) is an arbitrary choice.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] The summation is called a periodic summation of the function f {\displaystyle f} ({\displaystyle f}).
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] And if the periodic summation above is replaced by f T {\displaystyle f_{T}} ({\displaystyle f_{T}}), the operation is called a *periodic* convolution of f T {\displaystyle f_{T}} ({\displaystyle f_{T}}) and g T {\displaystyle g_{T}} ({\displaystyle g_{T}}).
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] The convolution of two finite sequences is defined by extending the sequences to finitely supported functions on the set of integers.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] When the sequences are the coefficients of two polynomials, then the coefficients of the ordinary product of the two polynomials are the convolution of the original two sequences.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] This is known as the Cauchy product of the coefficients of the sequences.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] The notation f ∗ N g {\displaystyle f*_{N}g} ({\displaystyle f*_{N}g}) for *cyclic convolution* denotes convolution over the cyclic group of integers modulo *N*.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Circular convolution arises most often in the context of fast convolution with a fast Fourier transform (FFT) algorithm.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] In many situations, discrete convolutions can be converted to circular convolutions so that fast transforms with a convolution property can be used to implement the computation.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] For example, convolution of digit sequences is the kernel operation in multiplication of multi-digit numbers, which can therefore be efficiently implemented with transform techniques (Knuth 1997, §4.3.3.C; von zur Gathen & Gerhard 2003, §8.2).
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] The most common fast convolution algorithms use fast Fourier transform (FFT) algorithms via the circular convolution theorem.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Specifically, the circular convolution of two finite-length sequences is found by taking an FFT of each sequence, multiplying pointwise, and then performing an inverse FFT.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Convolutions of the type defined above are then efficiently implemented using that technique in conjunction with zero-extension and/or discarding portions of the output.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Other fast convolution algorithms, such as the Schönhage–Strassen algorithm or the Mersenne transform, use fast Fourier transforms in other rings.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] The Winograd method is used as an alternative to the FFT.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] It significantly speeds up 1D, 2D, and 3D convolution.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] If one sequence is much longer than the other, zero-extension of the shorter sequence and fast circular convolution is not the most computationally efficient method available.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Instead, decomposing the longer sequence into blocks and convolving each block allows for faster algorithms such as the overlap–save method and overlap–add method.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] A hybrid convolution method that combines block and FIR algorithms allows for a zero input-output latency that is useful for real-time convolution computations.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] and is well-defined only if f and g decay sufficiently rapidly at infinity in order for the integral to exist.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Conditions for the existence of the convolution may be tricky, since a blow-up in g at infinity can be easily offset by sufficiently rapid decay in f.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] If f and g are compactly supported continuous functions, then their convolution exists, and is also compactly supported and continuous (Hörmander 1983, Chapter 1).
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] More generally, if either function (say f) is compactly supported and the other is locally integrable, then the convolution *f*∗*g* is well-defined and continuous.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Convolution of f and g is also well defined when both functions are locally square integrable on **R** and supported on an interval of the form [*a*, +∞) (or both supported on [−∞, *a*]).
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] The convolution of f and g exists if f and g are both Lebesgue integrable functions in *L*1(**R***d*), and in this case *f*∗*g* is also integrable (Stein & Weiss 1971, Theorem 1.3).
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] This is a consequence of Tonelli's theorem.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] This is also true for functions in *L*1, under the discrete convolution, or more generally for the convolution on any group.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] In the particular case *p* = 1, this shows that *L*1 is a Banach algebra under the convolution (and equality of the two sides holds if f and g are non-negative almost everywhere).
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] More generally, Young's inequality implies that the convolution is a continuous bilinear map between suitable *L**p* spaces.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] so that the convolution is a continuous bilinear mapping from *L**p*×*L**q* to *L**r*.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] The Young inequality for convolution is also true in other contexts (circle group, convolution on **Z**).
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] The optimal value of *B**p*,*q* was discovered in 1975 and independently in 1976, see Brascamp–Lieb inequality.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] In addition to compactly supported functions and integrable functions, functions that have sufficiently rapid decay at infinity can also be convolved.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] An important feature of the convolution is that if *f* and *g* both decay rapidly, then *f*∗*g* also decays rapidly.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] In particular, if *f* and *g* are rapidly decreasing functions, then so is the convolution *f*∗*g*.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Combined with the fact that convolution commutes with differentiation (see #Properties), it follows that the class of Schwartz functions is closed under convolution (Stein & Weiss 1971, Theorem 3.3).
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] remains valid in the case where *f* is a distribution, and *g* a compactly supported distribution (Hörmander 1983, §4.2).
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] where A ⊂ R d {\displaystyle A\subset \mathbf {R} ^{d}} ({\displaystyle A\subset \mathbf {R} ^{d}}) is a measurable set and 1 A {\displaystyle 1_{A}} ({\displaystyle 1_{A}}) is the indicator function of A {\displaystyle A} ({\displaystyle A}).
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] This agrees with the convolution defined above when μ and ν are regarded as distributions, as well as the convolution of L1 functions when μ and ν are absolutely continuous with respect to the Lebesgue measure.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] where the norm is the total variation of a measure.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Because the space of measures of bounded variation is a Banach space, convolution of measures can be treated with standard methods of functional analysis that may not apply for the convolution of distributions.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] The convolution defines a product on the linear space of integrable functions.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] This product satisfies the following algebraic properties, which formally mean that the space of integrable functions with the product given by convolution is a commutative associative algebra without identity (Strichartz 1994, §3.3).
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Other linear spaces of functions, such as the space of continuous functions of compact support, are closed under the convolution, and so also form commutative associative algebras.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] (i.e., double integrals can be evaluated as iterated integrals in either order).
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Proof: This follows from linearity of the integral.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] No algebra of functions possesses an identity for the convolution.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] The linear space of compactly supported distributions does, however, admit an identity under the convolution.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] The same result holds if *f* and *g* are only assumed to be nonnegative measurable functions, by Tonelli's theorem.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] where d d x {\displaystyle {\frac {d}{dx}}} ({\displaystyle {\frac {d}{dx}}}) is the derivative.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] A particular consequence of this is that the convolution can be viewed as a "smoothing" operation: the convolution of *f* and *g* is differentiable as many times as *f* and *g* are in total.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] These identities hold for example under the condition that *f* and *g* are absolutely integrable and at least one of them has an absolutely integrable (L1) weak derivative, as a consequence of Young's convolution inequality.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] These identities also hold much more broadly in the sense of tempered distributions if one of *f* or *g* is a rapidly decreasing tempered distribution, a compactly supported tempered distribution or a Schwartz function and the other is a tempered distribution.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] On the other hand, two positive integrable and infinitely differentiable functions may have a nowhere continuous convolution.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] where F { f } {\displaystyle {\mathcal {F}}\{f\}} ({\displaystyle {\mathcal {F}}\{f\}}) denotes the Fourier transform of f {\displaystyle f} ({\displaystyle f}).
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Versions of this theorem also hold for the Laplace transform, two-sided Laplace transform, Z-transform and Mellin transform.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] where ∙ {\displaystyle \bullet } ({\displaystyle \bullet }) is face-splitting product, ⊗ {\displaystyle \otimes } ({\displaystyle \otimes }) denotes Kronecker product, ∘ {\displaystyle \circ } ({\displaystyle \circ }) denotes Hadamard product (this result is an evolving of count sketch properties).
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] from the properties of the face-splitting product.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] If *f* is a Schwartz function, then *τxf* is the convolution with a translated Dirac delta function *τ**x**f* = *f* ∗ *τ**x* *δ*.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] So translation invariance of the convolution of Schwartz functions is a consequence of the associativity of convolution.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Furthermore, under certain conditions, convolution is the most general translation invariant operation.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Thus some translation invariant operations can be represented as convolution.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Convolutions play an important role in the study of time-invariant systems, and especially LTI system theory.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] The representing function *g**S* is the impulse response of the transformation *S*.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] A more precise version of the theorem quoted above requires specifying the class of functions on which the convolution is defined, and also requires assuming in addition that *S* must be a continuous linear operator with respect to the appropriate topology.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] It is known, for instance, that every continuous translation invariant continuous linear operator on *L*1 is the convolution with a finite Borel measure.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] More generally, every continuous translation invariant continuous linear operator on *L**p* for 1 ≤ *p* < ∞ is the convolution with a tempered distribution whose Fourier transform is bounded.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] To wit, they are all given by bounded Fourier multipliers.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] In typical cases of interest *G* is a locally compact Hausdorff topological group and λ is a (left-) Haar measure.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] In that case, unless *G* is unimodular, the convolution defined in this way is not the same as ∫ f ( x y − 1 ) g ( y ) d λ ( y ) {\textstyle \int f\left(xy^{-1}\right)g(y)\,d\lambda (y)} ({\textstyle \int f\left(xy^{-1}\right)g(y)\,d\lambda (y)}).
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Furthermore, the convention is also required for consistency with the definition of the convolution of measures given below.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] However, with a right instead of a left Haar measure, the latter integral is preferred over the former.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] On locally compact abelian groups, a version of the convolution theorem holds: the Fourier transform of a convolution is the pointwise product of the Fourier transforms.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] The circle group **T** with the Lebesgue measure is an immediate example.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] By the commutativity property cited above, *T* is normal: *T** *T* = *TT** .
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Also, *T* commutes with the translation operators.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Consider the family *S* of operators consisting of all such convolutions and the translation operators.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Then *S* is a commuting family of normal operators.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] According to spectral theory, there exists an orthonormal basis {*hk*} that simultaneously diagonalizes *S*.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] This characterizes convolutions on the circle.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] which are precisely the characters of **T**.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Each convolution is a compact multiplication operator in this basis.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] This can be viewed as a version of the convolution theorem discussed above.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] A discrete example is a finite cyclic group of order *n*.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Convolution operators are here represented by circulant matrices, and can be diagonalized by the discrete Fourier transform.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] Let *G* be a (multiplicatively written) topological group.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] In fact, if *either* measure is absolutely continuous with respect to the Haar measure, then so is their convolution.
[src:dsp/convolution-p01] If μ and ν are probability measures on the topological group (**R**,+), then the convolution *μ*∗*ν* is the probability distribution of the sum *X* + *Y* of two independent random variables *X* and *Y* whose respective distributions are μ and ν.
[src:dsp/convolution-p02] Let (*X*, Δ, ∇, *ε*, *η*) be a bialgebra with comultiplication Δ, multiplication ∇, unit η, and counit *ε*.
[src:dsp/convolution-p02] The convolution is a product defined on the endomorphism algebra End(*X*) as follows.
[src:dsp/convolution-p02] The convolution appears notably in the definition of Hopf algebras (Kassel 1995, §III.3).
[src:dsp/convolution-p02] Convolution and related operations are found in many applications in science, engineering and mathematics.
[src:dsp/convolution] In mathematics (in particular, functional analysis), **convolution** is a mathematical operation on two functions f and g that produces a third function $f*g$ , as the integral of the product of the two functions after one is reflected about the y-axis and shifted.
[src:dsp/convolution] The convolution of f and g is written $f*g$ , denoting the operator with the symbol * .
[src:dsp/convolution] While the symbol t is used above, it need not represent the time domain.
[src:dsp/convolution] At each t , the convolution formula can be described as the area under the function $f(\tau )$ weighted by the function $g(-\tau )$ shifted by the amount t .
[src:dsp/convolution] respectively, the convolution operation $(f*g)(t)$ can be defined as the inverse Laplace transform of the product of $F(s)$ and $G(s)$ .
[src:dsp/convolution] Note that $F(s)\cdot G(s)$ is the bilateral Laplace transform of $(f*g)(t)$ .
[src:dsp/convolution] The summation is called a periodic summation of the function f .
[src:dsp/convolution] When $g_{T}$ is a periodic summation of another function, g , then $f*g_{T}$ is known as a *circular* or *cyclic* convolution of f and g .
[src:dsp/convolution] And if the periodic summation above is replaced by $f_{T}$ , the operation is called a *periodic* convolution of $f_{T}$ and $g_{T}$ .
[src:dsp/convolution] The notation $f*_{N}g$ for *cyclic convolution* denotes convolution over the cyclic group of integers modulo *N*.
[src:dsp/convolution] where $A\subset \mathbf {R} ^{d}$ is a measurable set and $1_{A}$ is the indicator function of A .
[src:dsp/convolution] where ${\frac {d}{dx}}$ is the derivative.
[src:dsp/convolution] where ${\mathcal {F}}\{f\}$ denotes the Fourier transform of f .
[src:dsp/convolution] where $\bullet$ is face-splitting product, $\otimes$ denotes Kronecker product, $\circ$ denotes Hadamard product (this result is an evolving of count sketch properties).
[src:dsp/convolution] In that case, unless *G* is unimodular, the convolution defined in this way is not the same as ${\textstyle \int f\left(xy^{-1}\right)g(y)\,d\lambda (y)}$ .
[src:dsp/digital-filter] In signal processing, a **digital filter** is a system that performs mathematical operations on a sampled, discrete-time signal to reduce or enhance certain aspects of that signal.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] This is in contrast to the other major type of electronic filter, the analog filter, which is typically an electronic circuit operating on continuous-time analog signals.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] A digital filter system usually consists of an analog-to-digital converter (ADC) to sample the input signal, followed by a microprocessor and some peripheral components such as memory to store data and filter coefficients etc.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Program Instructions (software) running on the microprocessor implement the digital filter by performing the necessary mathematical operations on the numbers received from the ADC.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] In some high performance applications, an FPGA or ASIC is used instead of a general purpose microprocessor, or a specialized digital signal processor (DSP) with specific paralleled architecture for expediting operations such as filtering.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Digital filters may be more expensive than an equivalent analog filter due to their increased complexity, but they make practical many designs that are impractical or impossible as analog filters.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Digital filters can often be made very high order, and are often finite impulse response filters, which allows for linear phase response.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Digital filters are commonplace and an essential element of everyday electronics such as radios, cellphones, and AV receivers.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] A digital filter is characterized by its transfer function, or equivalently, its difference equation.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Mathematical analysis of the transfer function can describe how it will respond to any input.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] As such, designing a filter consists of developing specifications appropriate to the problem (for example, a second-order low-pass filter with a specific cut-off frequency), and then producing a transfer function that meets the specifications.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] where the order of the filter is the greater of *N* or *M*.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] See *Z*-transform's LCCD equation for further discussion of this transfer function.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] This is the form for a recursive filter, which typically leads to an infinite impulse response (IIR) behaviour, but if the denominator is made equal to unity, i.e. no feedback, then this becomes a finite impulse response (FIR) filter.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] A variety of mathematical techniques may be employed to analyze the behavior of a given digital filter.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Many of these analysis techniques may also be employed in designs, and often form the basis of a filter specification.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Typically, one characterizes filters by calculating how they will respond to a simple input such as an impulse.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] One can then extend this information to compute the filter's response to more complex signals.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] The impulse response, often denoted $h[k]$ or $h_{k}$ , is a measurement of how a filter will respond to the Kronecker delta function.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] For example, given a difference equation, one would set $x_{0}=1$ and $x_{k}=0$ for $k\neq 0$ and evaluate.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] The impulse response is a characterization of the filter's behavior.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Digital filters are typically considered in two categories: infinite impulse response (IIR) and finite impulse response (FIR).
[src:dsp/digital-filter] IIR filters on the other hand are recursive, with the output depending on both current and previous inputs as well as previous outputs.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Plotting the impulse response reveals how a filter responds to a sudden, momentary disturbance.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] While it is possible for a recursive filter to have a finite impulse response, a non-recursive filter always has a finite impulse response.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] An example is the moving average (MA) filter, which can be implemented both recursively and non recursively.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] In discrete-time systems, the digital filter is often implemented by converting the transfer function to a linear constant-coefficient difference equation (LCCD) via the Z-transform.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] The discrete frequency-domain transfer function is written as the ratio of two polynomials.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] The coefficients of the denominator, $a_{k}$ , are the 'feed-backward' coefficients and the coefficients of the numerator are the 'feed-forward' coefficients, $b_{k}$ .
[src:dsp/digital-filter] This equation shows how to compute the next output sample, $y[n]$ , in terms of the past outputs, $y[n-p]$ , the present input, $x[n]$ , and the past inputs, $x[n-p]$ .
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Applying the filter to an input in this form is equivalent to a Direct Form I or II (see below) realization, depending on the exact order of evaluation.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Although filters are easily understood and calculated, the practical challenges of their design and implementation are significant and are the subject of much advanced research.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] There are two categories of digital filter: the recursive filter and the nonrecursive filter.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] These are often referred to as IIR filters and FIR filters, respectively.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] After a filter is designed, it must be *realized* by developing a signal flow diagram that describes the filter in terms of operations on sample sequences.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] A given transfer function may be realized in many ways.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Consider how a simple expression such as $ax+bx+c$ could be evaluated – one could also compute the equivalent $x(a+b)+c$ .
[src:dsp/digital-filter] In the same way, all realizations may be seen as *factorizations* of the same transfer function, but different realizations will have different numerical properties.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Specifically, some realizations are more efficient in terms of the number of operations or storage elements required for their implementation, and others provide advantages such as improved numerical stability and reduced round-off error.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Some structures are better for fixed-point arithmetic and others may be better for floating-point arithmetic.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] A straightforward approach for IIR filter realization is direct form I, where the difference equation is evaluated directly.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] This form is practical for small filters, but may be inefficient and impractical (numerically unstable) for complex designs.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] In general, this form requires 2N delay elements (for both input and output signals) for a filter of order N.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] The alternate direct form II only needs *N* delay units, where *N* is the order of the filter – potentially half as much as direct form I.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] This structure is obtained by reversing the order of the numerator and denominator sections of Direct Form I, since they are in fact two linear systems, and the commutativity property applies.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Then, one will notice that there are two columns of delays ( $z^{-1}$ ) that tap off the center net, and these can be combined since they are redundant, yielding the implementation as shown below.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] The disadvantage is that direct form II increases the possibility of arithmetic overflow for filters of high *Q* or resonance.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] It has been shown that as *Q* increases, the round-off noise of both direct form topologies increases without bounds.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] This is because, conceptually, the signal is first passed through an all-pole filter (which normally boosts gain at the resonant frequencies) before the result of that is saturated, then passed through an all-zero filter (which often attenuates much of what the all-pole half amplifies).
[src:dsp/digital-filter] A common strategy is to realize a higher-order (greater than 2) digital filter as a cascaded series of second-order *biquadratric* (or *biquad*) sections (see digital biquad filter).
[src:dsp/digital-filter] The advantage of this strategy is that the coefficient range is limited.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Cascading direct form II sections results in *N* delay elements for filters of order *N*.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Cascading direct form I sections results in *N* + 2 delay elements, since the delay elements of the input of any section (except the first section) are redundant with the delay elements of the output of the preceding section.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Digital filters are not subject to the component tolerances, temperature variations, and non-linearities that greatly complicate the design of analog filters.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Analog filters consist of imperfect electronic components, whose values may also change with temperature and drift with time.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] As the order of an analog filter increases, and thus its component count, the effect of variable component errors is greatly magnified.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] In digital filters, the coefficient values are stored in computer memory, making them far more stable and predictable.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Because the coefficients of digital filters are definite, they can be used to achieve much more complex and selective designs – specifically with digital filters, one can achieve a lower passband ripple, faster transition, and higher stopband attenuation than is practical with analog filters.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Even if the design could be achieved using analog filters, the engineering cost of designing an equivalent digital filter would likely be much lower.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Furthermore, one can readily modify the coefficients of a digital filter to make an adaptive filter or a user-controllable parametric filter.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] While these techniques are possible in an analog filter, they are again considerably more difficult.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Digital filters can be used in the design of finite impulse response filters which can achieve extremely steep rolloff slopes with no phase shift.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Analog filters that perform the same function are often significantly more complicated, as they would require many delay elements.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Digital filters rely less on analog circuitry, potentially allowing for a better signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] A digital filter will introduce noise to a signal during analog low pass filtering, analog to digital conversion, digital to analog conversion and may introduce digital noise due to quantization.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] With analog filters, every component is a source of thermal noise (such as Johnson noise), so as the filter complexity grows, so does the noise.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] However, digital filters do introduce a higher fundamental latency to the system.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] In an analog filter, latency is often negligible; strictly speaking it is the time for an electrical signal to propagate through the filter circuit.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] In digital systems, latency is introduced not only by delay elements in the digital signal path, but also by analog-to-digital and digital-to-analog converters that are required for a system to process analog signals.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Digital filters must also deal with quantization and rounding errors.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Additionally, in very simple cases or in cases where frequencies and filter slopes are fixed, it is more cost effective to use an analog filter.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Introducing a digital filter requires considerable overhead circuitry, as previously discussed, including two low pass analog filters.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Analog filters also require substantially less power than digital filters and are therefore the only solution when power requirements are tight.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] When making an electrical circuit on a PCB it is generally easier to use a digital solution, because the processing units are highly optimized over the years.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Making the same circuit with analog components would take up a lot more space when using discrete components.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Two alternatives are FPAAs and ASICs, but they are expensive for low quantities.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] A filter can be represented by a block diagram, which can then be used to derive a sample processing algorithm to implement the filter with hardware instructions.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] A filter may also be described as a difference equation, a collection of zeros and poles or an impulse response or step response.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] These filters give O(n log n) computational costs whereas conventional digital filters tend to be O(n2).
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Another form of a digital filter is that of a state-space model.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] A well used state-space filter is the Kalman filter published by Rudolf Kálmán in 1960.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Traditional linear filters are usually based on attenuation.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Alternatively nonlinear filters can be designed, including energy transfer filters, which allow the user to move energy in a designed way so that unwanted noise or effects can be moved to new frequency bands either lower or higher in frequency, spread over a range of frequencies, split, or focused.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Energy transfer filters complement traditional filter designs and introduce many more degrees of freedom in filter design.
[src:dsp/digital-filter] Digital energy transfer filters are relatively easy to design and to implement and exploit nonlinear dynamics.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] Digital signal processing and analog signal processing are subfields of signal processing.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] DSP can involve linear or nonlinear operations.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] Nonlinear signal processing is closely related to nonlinear system identification and can be implemented in the time, frequency, and spatio-temporal domains.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] The application of digital computation to signal processing allows for many advantages over analog processing, in many applications, such as error detection and correction in transmission as well as data compression.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] Digital signal processing is also fundamental to digital technology, such as digital telecommunication and wireless communications.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] DSP is applicable to both streaming data and static (stored) data.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] To digitally analyze and manipulate an analog signal, it must be digitized with an analog-to-digital converter (ADC).
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] Sampling is usually carried out in two stages, discretization and quantization.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] Discretization means that the signal is divided into equal intervals of time, and each interval is represented by a single measurement of amplitude.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] Quantization means each amplitude measurement is approximated by a value from a finite set.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] Rounding real numbers to integers is an example.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] The Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem states that a signal can be exactly reconstructed from its samples if the sampling frequency is greater than twice the highest frequency component in the signal.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] In practice, the sampling frequency is often significantly higher than this.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] Theoretical DSP analyses and derivations are typically performed on discrete-time signal models with no amplitude inaccuracies (quantization error), created by the abstract process of sampling.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] Numerical methods require a quantized signal, such as those produced by an ADC.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] The processed result might be a frequency spectrum or a set of statistics.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] But often it is another quantized signal that is converted back to analog form by a digital-to-analog converter (DAC).
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] DSP engineers usually study digital signals in one of the following domains: time domain (one-dimensional signals), spatial domain (multidimensional signals), frequency domain, and wavelet domains.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] They choose the domain in which to process a signal by making an informed assumption (or by trying different possibilities) as to which domain best represents the essential characteristics of the signal and the processing to be applied to it.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] A sequence of samples from a measuring device produces a temporal or spatial domain representation, whereas a discrete Fourier transform produces the frequency domain representation.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] Time domain refers to the analysis of signals with respect to time.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] Similarly, the space domain refers to the analysis of signals with respect to position, e.g., pixel location for the case of image processing.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] The most common processing approach in the time or space domain is enhancement of the input signal through a method called filtering.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] Digital filtering generally consists of some linear transformation of a number of surrounding samples around the current sample of the input or output signal.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] The surrounding samples may be identified with respect to time or space.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] The output of a linear digital filter to any given input may be calculated by convolving the input signal with an impulse response.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] Signals are converted from the time or space domain to the frequency domain, usually through use of the Fourier transform.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] The Fourier transform converts the time or space information to a magnitude and phase component of each frequency.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] With some applications, how the phase varies with frequency can be a significant consideration.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] Where phase is unimportant, often the Fourier transform is converted to the power spectrum, which is the magnitude of each frequency component squared.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] The most common purpose for analysis of signals in the frequency domain is analysis of signal properties.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] The engineer can study the spectrum to determine which frequencies are present in the input signal and which are missing.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] Frequency domain analysis is also called *spectrum-* or *spectral analysis*.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] Filtering, particularly in non-realtime work, can also be achieved in the frequency domain, applying the filter and then converting back to the time domain.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] This can be an efficient implementation and can give essentially any filter response, including excellent approximations to brickwall filters.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] There are some commonly used frequency domain transformations.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] For example, the cepstrum converts a signal to the frequency domain through the Fourier transform, takes the logarithm, then applies another Fourier transform.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] This emphasizes the harmonic structure of the original spectrum.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] Digital filters come in both infinite impulse response (IIR) and finite impulse response (FIR) types.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] Whereas FIR filters are always stable, IIR filters have feedback loops that may become unstable and oscillate.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] The Z-transform provides a tool for analyzing stability issues of digital IIR filters.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] It is analogous to the Laplace transform, which is used to design and analyze analog IIR filters.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] A signal is represented as a linear combination of its previous samples.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] Coefficients of the combination are called autoregression coefficients.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] This method has higher frequency resolution and can process shorter signals compared to the Fourier transform.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] Prony's method can be used to estimate phases, amplitudes, initial phases and decays of the components of signal.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] Components are assumed to be complex decaying exponents.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] A time-frequency representation of a signal can capture both temporal evolution and frequency structure of the signal.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] Temporal and frequency resolution are limited by the uncertainty principle and the tradeoff is adjusted by the width of the analysis window.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] Linear techniques such as Short-time Fourier transform, wavelet transform, filter bank, non-linear (e.g., Wigner–Ville transform) and autoregressive methods (e.g. segmented Prony method) are used for representation of signal on the time-frequency plane.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] Non-linear and segmented Prony methods can provide higher resolution, but may produce undesirable artifacts.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] Time-frequency analysis is usually used for analysis of non-stationary signals.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] For example, methods of fundamental frequency estimation, such as RAPT and PEFAC are based on windowed spectral analysis.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] In numerical analysis and functional analysis, a discrete wavelet transform is any wavelet transform for which the wavelets are discretely sampled.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] As with other wavelet transforms, a key advantage it has over Fourier transforms is temporal resolution: it captures both frequency *and* location information.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] The accuracy of the joint time-frequency resolution is limited by the uncertainty principle of time-frequency.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] Empirical mode decomposition is based on decomposition of the signal into intrinsic mode functions (IMFs).
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] IMFs are quasi-harmonic oscillations that are extracted from the signal.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] DSP algorithms may be run on general-purpose computers and digital signal processors.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] DSP algorithms are also implemented on purpose-built hardware such as application-specific integrated circuit (ASICs).
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] Additional technologies for digital signal processing include more powerful general-purpose microprocessors, graphics processing units, field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs), digital signal controllers (mostly for industrial applications such as motor control), and stream processors.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] For systems that do not have a real-time computing requirement and the signal data (either input or output) exists in data files, processing may be done economically with a general-purpose computer.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] This is essentially no different from any other data processing, except that DSP mathematical techniques (such as the DCT and FFT) are used, and the sampled data is usually assumed to be uniformly sampled in time or space.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] An example of such an application is processing digital photographs with software such as Photoshop.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] When the application requirement is real-time, DSP is often implemented using specialized or dedicated processors or microprocessors, sometimes using multiple processors or multiple processing cores.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] These may process data using fixed- or floating-point arithmetic.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] For more demanding applications, FPGAs may be used.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] For the most demanding applications or high-volume products, ASICs might be designed specifically for the application.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] Parallel implementations of DSP algorithms, utilizing multi-core CPU and many-core GPU architectures, are developed to improve the performance in terms of latency of these algorithms.
[src:dsp/digital-signal-processing] DSP has been used in hearing aid technology since 1996, which allows for automatic directional microphones, complex digital noise reduction, and improved adjustment of the frequency response.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] In mathematics, the **discrete Fourier transform** (**DFT**) is a discrete version of the Fourier transform that converts a finite sequence of numbers into another sequence of the same length, representing the amplitude and phase of different frequency components.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] In this way, it changes data from a description in terms of sampled values to a description in terms of oscillations.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The inverse discrete Fourier transform reverses this process and recovers the original sequence.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] For data sampled at equally spaced points, the DFT can be understood more precisely as converting between sample values and the coefficients of a trigonometric polynomial that interpolates those values.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] It is therefore a basic tool for numerical work with smooth periodic functions, which can often be approximated well by trigonometric polynomials.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] In practice, the DFT is usually computed by efficient fast Fourier transform (FFT) algorithms.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The DFT is used in many practical applications of Fourier analysis.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] In digital signal processing, the input is often a sampled quantity or signal that varies over time, such as the pressure of a sound wave, a radio signal, or daily temperature readings, sampled over a finite time interval (often defined by a window function).
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] In image processing, the samples can be the values of pixels along a row or column of a raster image.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The DFT is also used to efficiently solve partial differential equations, and to perform other operations such as convolutions or multiplying large integers.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Since the DFT deals with a finite amount of data, it can be implemented in computers by numerical algorithms or even dedicated hardware.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] These implementations usually employ efficient fast Fourier transform (FFT) algorithms; so much so that the terms "FFT" and "DFT" are often used interchangeably.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Prior to its current usage, the "FFT" initialism may have also been used for the ambiguous term "finite Fourier transform".
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The transform is sometimes denoted by the symbol ${\mathcal {F}}$ , as in $\mathbf {X} ={\mathcal {F}}\left\{\mathbf {x} \right\}$ or ${\mathcal {F}}\left(\mathbf {x} \right)$ or ${\mathcal {F}}\mathbf {x}$ .
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] As a linear transformation on a finite-dimensional vector space, the DFT expression can also be written in terms of a DFT matrix.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] When scaled appropriately, it becomes a unitary matrix, and the DFT can thus be viewed as a transformation from one orthonormal basis to another.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The normalization factor multiplying the DFT and inverse DFT (IDFT), here 1 and ${\tfrac {1}{N}}$ , and the signs of the exponents are the most common conventions.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The only actual requirements of these conventions are that the DFT and IDFT have opposite-sign exponents and that the product of their normalization factors be ${\tfrac {1}{N}}.$ An uncommon normalization of ${\sqrt {\tfrac {1}{N}}}$ for both the DFT and IDFT makes the transform-pair unitary.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Using the standard definition of the DFT omits the sampling interval (or sampling distance) $\Delta t$ in cases where the index corresponds to time via $n\Delta t=t$ .
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Most software libraries compute the unscaled DFT coefficients $X_{k}$ , including their corresponding FFT implementations.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The scaled coefficients can therefore be obtained as ${\tilde {X}}_{k}=\Delta t\cdot X_{k}$ .
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] When applying the DFT to physical data, the sampling interval $\Delta t$ (or equivalently $\Delta f$ ) is an essential part of the signal definition.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Including the sampling interval ensures correct amplitude, energy, and frequency interpretation, particularly when combining or comparing data from different sources.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The DFT can be regarded as transforming a finite sequence of equally-spaced samples of a function into a same-length sequence of equally-spaced samples of the discrete-time Fourier transform (DTFT), which is a complex-valued function of frequency.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The interval at which the DTFT is sampled is the reciprocal of the duration of the input sequence.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] An inverse DFT (IDFT) is a Fourier series, using the DTFT samples as coefficients of complex sinusoids at the corresponding DTFT frequencies.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] It has the same sample-values as the original input sequence.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The DFT is therefore said to be a frequency domain representation of the original input sequence.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] If the original sequence spans all the non-zero values of a function, its DTFT is continuous (and periodic), and the DFT provides discrete samples of one cycle.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] If the original sequence is one cycle of a periodic function, the DFT provides all the non-zero values of one DTFT cycle.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Reversing the time (i.e. replacing n by $N-n$ ) in $x_{n}$ corresponds to reversing the frequency (i.e. k by $N-k$ ).
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] This table shows some mathematical operations on $x_{n}$ in the time domain and the corresponding effects on its DFT $X_{k}$ in the frequency domain.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] where $\delta _{kk'}$ is the Kronecker delta.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] where the star denotes complex conjugation.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] These theorems are also equivalent to the unitary condition below.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Similarly, it can be shown that the IDFT formula leads to a periodic extension of $x_{n}$ .
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Multiplying $x_{n}$ by a *linear phase* $e^{{\frac {i2\pi }{N}}nm}$ for some integer *m* corresponds to a *circular shift* of the output $X_{k}$ : $X_{k}$ is replaced by $X_{k-m}$ , where the subscript is interpreted modulo *N* (i.e., periodically).
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Similarly, a circular shift of the input $x_{n}$ corresponds to multiplying the output $X_{k}$ by a linear phase.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The convolution theorem for the discrete-time Fourier transform (DTFT) indicates that a convolution of two sequences can be obtained as the inverse transform of the product of the individual transforms.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Customarily, the DFT and inverse DFT summations are taken over the domain $[0,N-1]$ .
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] which gives rise to the interpretation as a *circular* convolution of x and $y.$ It is often used to efficiently compute their linear convolution.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] As seen above, the discrete Fourier transform has the fundamental property of carrying convolution into componentwise product.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] A natural question is whether it is the only one with this ability.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] It has been shown that any linear transform that turns convolution into pointwise product is the DFT up to a permutation of coefficients.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Since the number of permutations of n elements equals n!, there exist exactly n! linear and invertible maps with the same fundamental property as the DFT with respect to convolution.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] where the coefficients *X**k* are given by the DFT of *x**n* above, satisfies the interpolation property $p(n/N)=x_{n}$ for $n=0,\ldots ,N-1$ .
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] For even *N*, notice that the Nyquist component ${\textstyle {\frac {X_{N/2}}{N}}\cos(N\pi t)}$ is handled specially.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] This interpolation is *not unique*: aliasing implies that one could add *N* to any of the complex-sinusoid frequencies (e.g. changing $e^{-it}$ to $e^{i(N-1)t}$ ) without changing the interpolation property, but giving *different* values in between the $x_{n}$ points.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The choice above, however, is typical because it has two useful properties.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] First, it consists of sinusoids whose frequencies have the smallest possible magnitudes: the interpolation is bandlimited.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Second, if the $x_{n}$ are real numbers, then $p(t)$ is real as well.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] In contrast, the most obvious trigonometric interpolation polynomial is the one in which the frequencies range from 0 to $N-1$ (instead of roughly $-N/2$ to $+N/2$ as above), similar to the inverse DFT formula.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] This interpolation does *not* minimize the slope, and is *not* generally real-valued for real $x_{n}$ ; its use is a common mistake.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] where $\omega _{N}=e^{-i2\pi /N}$ is a primitive *N*th root of unity.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] where $\det()$ is the determinant function.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The determinant is the product of the eigenvalues, which are always $\pm 1$ or $\pm i$ as described below.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] In a real vector space, a unitary transformation can be thought of as simply a rigid rotation of the coordinate system, and all of the properties of a rigid rotation can be found in the unitary DFT.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] If we view the DFT as just a coordinate transformation which simply specifies the components of a vector in a new coordinate system, then the above is just the statement that the dot product of two vectors is preserved under a unitary DFT transformation.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] A consequence of the circular convolution theorem is that the DFT matrix F diagonalizes any circulant matrix.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] A useful property of the DFT is that the inverse DFT can be easily expressed in terms of the (forward) DFT, via several well-known "tricks".
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Third, a variant of this conjugation trick, which is sometimes preferable because it requires no modification of the data values, involves swapping real and imaginary parts (which can be done on a computer simply by modifying pointers).
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Define ${\textstyle \operatorname {swap} (x_{n})}$ as $x_{n}$ with its real and imaginary parts swapped—that is, if $x_{n}=a+bi$ then ${\textstyle \operatorname {swap} (x_{n})}$ is $b+ai$ .
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] That is, the inverse transform is the same as the forward transform with the real and imaginary parts swapped for both input and output, up to a normalization.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The conjugation trick can also be used to define a new transform, closely related to the DFT, that is involutory—that is, which is its own inverse.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] For real inputs $\mathbf {x}$ , the real part of $H(\mathbf {x} )$ is none other than the discrete Hartley transform, which is also involutory.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The eigenvalues of the DFT matrix are simple and well-known, whereas the eigenvectors are complicated, not unique, and are the subject of ongoing research.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Explicit formulas are given with a significant amount of number theory.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] This can be seen from the inverse properties above: operating $\mathbf {U}$ twice gives the original data in reverse order, so operating $\mathbf {U}$ four times gives back the original data and is thus the identity matrix.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Therefore, the eigenvalues of $\mathbf {U}$ are the fourth roots of unity: $\lambda$ is +1, −1, +*i*, or −*i*.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Since there are only four distinct eigenvalues for this $N\times N$ matrix, they have some multiplicity.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The multiplicity gives the number of linearly independent eigenvectors corresponding to each eigenvalue.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The problem of their multiplicity was solved by McClellan and Parks (1972), although it was later shown to have been equivalent to a problem solved by Gauss (Dickinson and Steiglitz, 1982).
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] No simple analytical formula for general eigenvectors is known.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Moreover, the eigenvectors are not unique because any linear combination of eigenvectors for the same eigenvalue is also an eigenvector for that eigenvalue.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] hence, vector $\mathbf {u} (\lambda )$ is, indeed, the eigenvector of DFT matrix $\mathbf {U}$ .
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Operators ${\mathcal {P}}_{\lambda }$ project vectors onto subspaces which are orthogonal for each value of $\lambda$ .
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] However, in general, projection operator method does not produce orthogonal eigenvectors within one subspace.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The operator ${\mathcal {P}}_{\lambda }$ can be seen as a matrix, whose columns are eigenvectors of $\mathbf {U}$ , but they are not orthogonal.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] However, the orthogonal set can be obtained by further applying orthogonalization algorithm to the set $\{\mathbf {u} _{n}(\lambda )\}_{n=1,\dots ,N_{\lambda }}$ , e.g.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] A straightforward approach to obtain DFT eigenvectors is to discretize an eigenfunction of the continuous Fourier transform, of which the most famous is the Gaussian function.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The choice of eigenvectors of the DFT matrix has become important in recent years in order to define a discrete analogue of the fractional Fourier transform—the DFT matrix can be taken to fractional powers by exponentiating the eigenvalues.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] For the continuous Fourier transform, the natural orthogonal eigenfunctions are the Hermite functions, so various discrete analogues of these have been employed as the eigenvectors of the DFT, such as the Kravchuk polynomials.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The "best" choice of eigenvectors to define a fractional discrete Fourier transform remains an open question, however.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Attempts were made to perform the fractional Fourier transform using confluent Vandermonde matrix.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] where $D_{0}(X)$ and $D_{0}(x)$ are the variances of $|X|^{2}$ and $|x|^{2}$ respectively, with the equality attained in the case of a suitably normalized Gaussian distribution.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Although the variances may be analogously defined for the DFT, an analogous uncertainty principle is not useful, because the uncertainty will not be shift-invariant.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Still, a meaningful uncertainty principle has been introduced by Massar and Spindel.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] However, the Hirschman entropic uncertainty will have a useful analog for the case of the DFT.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The Hirschman uncertainty principle is expressed in terms of the Shannon entropy of the two probability functions.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The equality is obtained for $P_{n}$ equal to translations and modulations of a suitably normalized Kronecker comb of period A where A is any exact integer divisor of N .
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The probability mass function $Q_{m}$ will then be proportional to a suitably translated Kronecker comb of period $B=N/A$ .
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] There is also a well-known deterministic uncertainty principle that uses signal sparsity (or the number of non-zero coefficients).
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] As an immediate consequence of the inequality of arithmetic and geometric means, one also has $2{\sqrt {N}}\leq \left\|x\right\|_{0}+\left\|X\right\|_{0}$ .
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Both uncertainty principles were shown to be tight for specifically chosen "picket-fence" sequences (discrete impulse trains), and find practical use for signal recovery applications.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] It follows that for even N $X_{0}$ and $X_{N/2}$ are real-valued, and the remainder of the DFT is completely specified by just $N/2-1$ complex numbers.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] It is possible to shift the transform sampling in time and/or frequency domain by some real shifts *a* and *b*, respectively.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Most often, shifts of $1/2$ (half a sample) are used.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] While the ordinary DFT corresponds to a periodic signal in both time and frequency domains, $a=1/2$ produces a signal that is anti-periodic in frequency domain ( $X_{k+N}=-X_{k}$ ) and vice versa for $b=1/2$ .
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Thus, the specific case of $a=b=1/2$ is known as an *odd-time odd-frequency* discrete Fourier transform (or O2 DFT).
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Such shifted transforms are most often used for symmetric data, to represent different boundary symmetries, and for real-symmetric data they correspond to different forms of the discrete cosine and sine transforms.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Another interesting choice is $a=b=-(N-1)/2$ , which is called the **centered DFT** (or **CDFT**).
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The centered DFT has the useful property that, when *N* is a multiple of four, all four of its eigenvalues (see above) have equal multiplicities.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The term GDFT is also used for the non-linear phase extensions of DFT.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Hence, GDFT method provides a generalization for constant amplitude orthogonal block transforms including linear and non-linear phase types.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] GDFT is a framework to improve time and frequency domain properties of the traditional DFT, e.g. auto/cross-correlations, by the addition of the properly designed phase shaping function (non-linear, in general) to the original linear phase functions.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The discrete Fourier transform can be viewed as a special case of the z-transform, evaluated on the unit circle in the complex plane; more general z-transforms correspond to *complex* shifts *a* and *b* above.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The ordinary DFT transforms a one-dimensional sequence or array $x_{n}$ that is a function of exactly one discrete variable *n*.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] where the division $\mathbf {n} /\mathbf {N}$ is defined as $\mathbf {n} /\mathbf {N} =(n_{1}/N_{1},\dots ,n_{d}/N_{d})$ to be performed element-wise, and the sum denotes the set of nested summations above.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] As the one-dimensional DFT expresses the input $x_{n}$ as a superposition of sinusoids, the multidimensional DFT expresses the input as a superposition of plane waves, or multidimensional sinusoids.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The direction of oscillation in space is $\mathbf {k} /\mathbf {N}$ .
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] This decomposition is of great importance for everything from digital image processing (two-dimensional) to solving partial differential equations.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The solution is broken up into plane waves.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The multidimensional DFT can be computed by the composition of a sequence of one-dimensional DFTs along each dimension.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] In the two-dimensional case $x_{n_{1},n_{2}}$ the $N_{1}$ independent DFTs of the rows (i.e., along $n_{2}$ ) are computed first to form a new array $y_{n_{1},k_{2}}$ .
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Then the $N_{2}$ independent DFTs of *y* along the columns (along $n_{1}$ ) are computed to form the final result $X_{k_{1},k_{2}}$ .
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Alternatively the columns can be computed first and then the rows.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The order is immaterial because the nested summations above commute.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] An algorithm to compute a one-dimensional DFT is thus sufficient to efficiently compute a multidimensional DFT.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] This approach is known as the *row-column* algorithm.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] There are also intrinsically multidimensional FFT algorithms.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] where the star again denotes complex conjugation and the $\ell$ -th subscript is again interpreted modulo $N_{\ell }$ (for $\ell =1,2,\ldots ,d$ ).
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The DFT has seen wide usage across a large number of fields; we only sketch a few examples below (see also the references at the end).
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] All applications of the DFT depend crucially on the availability of a fast algorithm to compute discrete Fourier transforms and their inverses, a fast Fourier transform.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] When the DFT is used for signal spectral analysis, the $\{x_{n}\}$ sequence usually represents a finite set of uniformly spaced time-samples of some signal $x(t)\,$ , where t represents time.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The conversion from continuous time to samples (discrete-time) changes the underlying Fourier transform of $x(t)$ into a discrete-time Fourier transform (DTFT), which generally entails a type of distortion called aliasing.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Choice of an appropriate sample-rate (see *Nyquist rate*) is the key to minimizing that distortion.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Similarly, the conversion from a very long (or infinite) sequence to a manageable size entails a type of distortion called *leakage*, which is manifested as a loss of detail (a.k.a. resolution) in the DTFT.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Choice of an appropriate sub-sequence length is the primary key to minimizing that effect.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] When the available data (and time to process it) is more than the amount needed to attain the desired frequency resolution, a standard technique is to perform multiple DFTs, for example to create a spectrogram.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] A final source of distortion (or perhaps *illusion*) is the DFT itself, because it is just a discrete sampling of the DTFT, which is a function of a continuous frequency domain.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] That can be mitigated by increasing the resolution of the DFT.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] That procedure is illustrated at § Sampling the DTFT.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The discrete Fourier transform is widely used with spatial frequencies in modeling the way that light, electrons, and other probes travel through optical systems and scatter from objects in two and three dimensions.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] See § FFT filter banks and § Sampling the DTFT.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The field of digital signal processing relies heavily on operations in the frequency domain (i.e. on the Fourier transform).
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] For example, several lossy image and sound compression methods employ the discrete Fourier transform: the signal is cut into short segments, each is transformed, and then the Fourier coefficients of high frequencies, which are assumed to be unnoticeable, are discarded.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The decompressor computes the inverse transform based on this reduced number of Fourier coefficients.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Some relatively recent compression algorithms, however, use wavelet transforms, which give a more uniform compromise between time and frequency domain than obtained by chopping data into segments and transforming each segment.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] In the case of JPEG2000, this avoids the spurious image features that appear when images are highly compressed with the original JPEG.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Discrete Fourier transforms are often used to solve partial differential equations, where again the DFT is used as an approximation for the Fourier series (which is recovered in the limit of infinite *N*).
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The advantage of this approach is that it expands the signal in complex exponentials $e^{inx}$ , which are eigenfunctions of differentiation: ${{\text{d}}{\big (}e^{inx}{\big )}}/{\text{d}}x=ine^{inx}$ .
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Thus, in the Fourier representation, differentiation is simple—we just multiply by $in$ .
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] (However, the choice of n is not unique due to aliasing; for the method to be convergent, a choice similar to that in the trigonometric interpolation section above should be used.) A linear differential equation with constant coefficients is transformed into an easily solvable algebraic equation.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] One then uses the inverse DFT to transform the result back into the ordinary spatial representation.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Such an approach is called a spectral method.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Suppose we wish to compute the polynomial product *c*(*x*) = *a*(*x*) · *b*(*x*).
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Here the vector product is taken elementwise.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] With a fast Fourier transform, the resulting algorithm takes *O*(*N* log *N*) arithmetic operations.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Due to its simplicity and speed, the Cooley–Tukey FFT algorithm, which is limited to composite sizes, is often chosen for the transform operation.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] In this case, *d* should be chosen as the smallest integer greater than the sum of the input polynomial degrees that is factorizable into small prime factors (e.g.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] 2, 3, and 5, depending upon the FFT implementation).
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] The fastest known algorithms for the multiplication of very large integers use the polynomial multiplication method outlined above.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Integers can be treated as the value of a polynomial evaluated specifically at the number base, with the coefficients of the polynomial corresponding to the digits in that base (ex. $123=1\cdot 10^{2}+2\cdot 10^{1}+3\cdot 10^{0}$ ).
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] After polynomial multiplication, a relatively low-complexity carry-propagation step completes the multiplication.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] When data is convolved with a function with wide support, such as for downsampling by a large sampling ratio, because of the Convolution theorem and the FFT algorithm, it may be faster to transform it, multiply pointwise by the transform of the filter and then reverse transform it.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p01] Alternatively, a good filter is obtained by simply truncating the transformed data and re-transforming the shortened data set.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] The DFT can be interpreted as a complex-valued representation of the finite cyclic group.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] In other words, a sequence of n complex numbers can be thought of as an element of n -dimensional complex space $\mathbb {C} ^{n}$ or equivalently a function f from the finite cyclic group of order n to the complex numbers, $\mathbb {Z} _{n}\mapsto \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] So f is a class function on the finite cyclic group, and thus can be expressed as a linear combination of the irreducible characters of this group, which are the roots of unity.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] From this point of view, one may generalize the DFT to representation theory generally, or more narrowly to the representation theory of finite groups.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] More narrowly still, one may generalize the DFT by either changing the target (taking values in a field other than the complex numbers), or the domain (a group other than a finite cyclic group), as detailed in the sequel.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] Many of the properties of the DFT only depend on the fact that $e^{-{\frac {i2\pi }{N}}}$ is a primitive root of unity, sometimes denoted $\omega _{N}$ or $W_{N}$ (so that $\omega _{N}^{N}=1$ ).
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] Such properties include the completeness, orthogonality, Plancherel/Parseval, periodicity, shift, convolution, and unitarity properties above, as well as many FFT algorithms.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] For this reason, the discrete Fourier transform can be defined by using roots of unity in fields other than the complex numbers, and such generalizations are commonly called *number-theoretic transforms* (NTTs) in the case of finite fields.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] For more information, see number-theoretic transform and discrete Fourier transform (general).
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] The standard DFT acts on a sequence *x*0, *x*1, ..., *x**N*−1 of complex numbers, which can be viewed as a function {0, 1, ..., *N* − 1} → **C**.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] This suggests the generalization to Fourier transforms on arbitrary finite groups, which act on functions *G* → **C** where *G* is a finite group.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] In this framework, the standard DFT is seen as the Fourier transform on a cyclic group, while the multidimensional DFT is a Fourier transform on a direct sum of cyclic groups.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] Further, Fourier transform can be on cosets of a group.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] There are various alternatives to the DFT for various applications, prominent among which are wavelets.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] The analog of the DFT is the discrete wavelet transform (DWT).
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] From the point of view of time–frequency analysis, a key limitation of the Fourier transform is that it does not include *location* information, only *frequency* information, and thus has difficulty in representing transients.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] As wavelets have location as well as frequency, they are better able to represent location, at the expense of greater difficulty representing frequency.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p02] For details, see comparison of the discrete wavelet transform with the discrete Fourier transform.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p03] The ordinary DFT transforms a one-dimensional sequence or array x n {\displaystyle x_{n}} ({\displaystyle x_{n}}) that is a function of exactly one discrete variable *n*.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p03] As the one-dimensional DFT expresses the input x n {\displaystyle x_{n}} ({\displaystyle x_{n}}) as a superposition of sinusoids, the multidimensional DFT expresses the input as a superposition of plane waves, or multidimensional sinusoids.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p03] The direction of oscillation in space is k / N {\displaystyle \mathbf {k} /\mathbf {N} } ({\displaystyle \mathbf {k} /\mathbf {N} }).
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p03] The amplitudes are X k {\displaystyle X_{\mathbf {k} }} ({\displaystyle X_{\mathbf {k} }}).
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p03] Then the N 2 {\displaystyle N_{2}} ({\displaystyle N_{2}}) independent DFTs of *y* along the columns (along n 1 {\displaystyle n_{1}} ({\displaystyle n_{1}})) are computed to form the final result X k 1 , k 2 {\displaystyle X_{k_{1},k_{2}}} ({\displaystyle X_{k_{1},k_{2}}}).
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p03] The conversion from continuous time to samples (discrete-time) changes the underlying Fourier transform of x ( t ) {\displaystyle x(t)} ({\displaystyle x(t)}) into a discrete-time Fourier transform (DTFT), which generally entails a type of distortion called aliasing.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p03] Thus, in the Fourier representation, differentiation is simple—we just multiply by i n {\displaystyle in} ({\displaystyle in}).
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p03] Integers can be treated as the value of a polynomial evaluated specifically at the number base, with the coefficients of the polynomial corresponding to the digits in that base (ex.
[src:dsp/discrete-fourier-transform-p03] So f {\displaystyle f} ({\displaystyle f}) is a class function on the finite cyclic group, and thus can be expressed as a linear combination of the irreducible characters of this group, which are the roots of unity.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] A **fast Fourier transform** (**FFT**) is an algorithm that computes the discrete Fourier transform (DFT), or its inverse (IDFT), of a sequence.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] A Fourier transform converts a signal from its original domain (often time or space) to a representation in the frequency domain and vice versa.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] The DFT is obtained by decomposing a sequence of values into components of different frequencies.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] This operation is useful in many fields, but computing it directly from the definition is often too slow to be practical.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] An FFT rapidly computes such transformations by factorizing the DFT matrix into a product of sparse (mostly zero) factors.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] As a result, it manages to reduce the complexity of computing the DFT from ${\textstyle O(n^{2})}$ , which arises if one simply applies the definition of DFT, to ${\textstyle O(n\log n)}$ , where n is the length of the sequence.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] The difference in speed can be enormous, especially for long sequences where n may be in the thousands or millions.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] As the FFT is merely an algebraic refactoring of terms within the DFT, the DFT and the FFT both perform mathematically equivalent and interchangeable operations, assuming that all terms are computed with infinite precision.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] However, in the presence of round-off error, many FFT algorithms are much more accurate than evaluating the DFT definition directly or indirectly.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] There are many different FFT algorithms based on a wide range of published theories, from simple complex-number arithmetic to group theory and number theory.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] The best-known FFT algorithms depend upon the factorization of n, but there are FFTs with $O(n\log n)$ complexity for all n, including prime values.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Many FFT algorithms depend only on the fact that ${\textstyle e^{-2\pi i/n}}$ is an nth primitive root of unity, and thus can be applied to analogous transforms over any finite field, such as number-theoretic transforms.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Since the inverse DFT is the same as the DFT, but with the opposite sign in the exponent and a 1/*n* factor, any FFT algorithm can easily be adapted for it.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Fast Fourier transforms are widely used for applications in engineering, music, science, and mathematics.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] The basic ideas were popularized in 1965, but some algorithms had been derived as early as 1805.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] In 1994, Gilbert Strang described the FFT as "the most important numerical algorithm of our lifetime", and it was included in Top 10 Algorithms of 20th Century by the IEEE magazine *Computing in Science & Engineering*.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] The development of fast algorithms for DFT was prefigured in Carl Friedrich Gauss's unpublished 1805 work on the orbits of asteroids Pallas and Juno.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Gauss wanted to interpolate the orbits from sample observations; his method was very similar to the one that would be published in 1965 by James Cooley and John Tukey, who are generally credited for the invention of the modern generic FFT algorithm.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] While Gauss's work predated even Joseph Fourier's 1822 results, he did not analyze the method's complexity, and eventually used other methods to achieve the same end.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Between 1805 and 1965, some versions of FFT were published by other authors.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Frank Yates in 1932 published his version called *interaction algorithm*, which provided efficient computation of Hadamard and Walsh transforms.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Yates' algorithm is still used in the field of statistical design and analysis of experiments.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Danielson and Cornelius Lanczos published their version to compute DFT for x-ray crystallography, a field where calculation of Fourier transforms presented a formidable bottleneck.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Good published a paper establishing the prime-factor FFT algorithm that applies to discrete Fourier transforms of size ${\textstyle n=n_{1}n_{2}}$ , where $n_{1}$ and $n_{2}$ are coprime.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] James Cooley and John Tukey independently rediscovered these earlier algorithms and published a more general FFT in 1965 that is applicable when n is composite and not necessarily a power of 2, as well as analyzing the ${\textstyle O(n\log n)}$ scaling.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Tukey came up with the idea during a meeting of President Kennedy's Science Advisory Committee, where a discussion topic involved detecting nuclear tests by the Soviet Union by setting up sensors to surround the country from outside.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] To analyze the output of these sensors, an FFT algorithm would be needed.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] In discussion with Tukey, Richard Garwin recognized the general applicability of the algorithm not just to national security problems, but also to a wide range of problems including one of immediate interest to him, determining the periodicities of the spin orientations in a 3-D crystal of Helium-3.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Garwin gave Tukey's idea to Cooley (both worked at IBM's Watson labs) for implementation.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Cooley and Tukey published the paper in a relatively short time of six months.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] As Tukey did not work at IBM, the patentability of the idea was doubted and the algorithm went into the public domain, which, through the computing revolution of the next decade, made FFT one of the indispensable algorithms in digital signal processing.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] where $e^{i2\pi /n}$ is a primitive nth root of 1.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Evaluating this definition directly requires ${\textstyle O(n^{2})}$ operations: there are n outputs Xk , and each output requires a sum of n terms.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] An FFT is any method to compute the same results in ${\textstyle O(n\log n)}$ operations.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] All known FFT algorithms require ${\textstyle O(n\log n)}$ operations, although there is no known proof that lower complexity is impossible.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] To illustrate the savings of an FFT, consider the count of complex multiplications and additions for ${\textstyle n=4096}$ data points.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Evaluating the DFT's sums directly involves ${\textstyle n^{2}}$ complex multiplications and ${\textstyle n(n-1)}$ complex additions, of which ${\textstyle O(n)}$ operations can be saved by eliminating trivial operations such as multiplications by 1, leaving about 30 million operations.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] By far the most commonly used FFT is the Cooley–Tukey algorithm.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] The best known use of the Cooley–Tukey algorithm is to divide the transform into two pieces of size *n*/2 at each step, and is therefore limited to power-of-two sizes, but any factorization can be used in general (as was known to both Gauss and Cooley/Tukey).
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] These are called the *radix-2* and *mixed-radix* cases, respectively (and other variants such as the split-radix FFT have their own names as well).
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Although the basic idea is recursive, most traditional implementations rearrange the algorithm to avoid explicit recursion.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Also, because the Cooley–Tukey algorithm breaks the DFT into smaller DFTs, it can be combined arbitrarily with any other algorithm for the DFT, such as those described below.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] For ${\textstyle n=n_{1}n_{2}}$ with coprime ${\textstyle n_{1}}$ and ${\textstyle n_{2}}$ , one can use the prime-factor (Good–Thomas) algorithm (PFA), based on the Chinese remainder theorem, to factorize the DFT similarly to Cooley–Tukey but without the twiddle factors.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Algorithms that recursively factorize the DFT into smaller operations other than DFTs include the Bruun and QFT algorithms.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] (The Rader–Brenner and QFT algorithms were proposed for power-of-two sizes, but it is possible that they could be adapted to general composite n.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Bruun's algorithm applies to arbitrary even composite sizes.) Bruun's algorithm, in particular, is based on interpreting the FFT as a recursive factorization of the polynomial $z^{n}-1$ , here into real-coefficient polynomials of the form $z^{m}-1$ and $z^{2m}+az^{m}+1$ .
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] In particular, Winograd also makes use of the PFA as well as an algorithm by Rader for FFTs of *prime* sizes.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Hexagonal fast Fourier transform (HFFT) aims at computing an efficient FFT for the hexagonally-sampled data by using a new addressing scheme for hexagonal grids, called Array Set Addressing (ASA).
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] and efficient FFT algorithms have been designed for this situation (see e.g., Sorensen, 1987).
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] One approach consists of taking an ordinary algorithm (e.g., Cooley–Tukey) and removing the redundant parts of the computation, saving roughly a factor of two in time and memory.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Alternatively, it is possible to express an *even*-length real-input DFT as a complex DFT of half the length (whose real and imaginary parts are the even/odd elements of the original real data), followed by $O(n)$ post-processing operations.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Bruun's algorithm (above) is another method that was initially proposed to take advantage of real inputs, but it has not proved popular.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] There are further FFT specializations for the cases of real data that have even/odd symmetry, in which case one can gain another factor of roughly two in time and memory and the DFT becomes the discrete cosine/sine transform(s) (DCT/DST).
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Instead of directly modifying an FFT algorithm for these cases, DCTs/DSTs can also be computed via FFTs of real data combined with $O(n)$ pre- and post-processing.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] What is the lower bound on the complexity of fast Fourier transform algorithms?
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] A fundamental question of longstanding theoretical interest is to prove lower bounds on the complexity and exact operation counts of fast Fourier transforms, and many open problems remain.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] It is not rigorously proved whether DFTs truly require ${\textstyle \Omega (n\log n)}$ (i.e., order *$n\log n$* or greater) operations, even for the simple case of power of two sizes, although no algorithms with lower complexity are known.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] In particular, the count of arithmetic operations is usually the focus of such questions, although actual performance on modern-day computers is determined by many other factors such as cache or CPU pipeline optimization.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Following work by Shmuel Winograd (1978), a tight $\Theta (n)$ lower bound is known for the number of real multiplications required by an FFT.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] It can be shown that only ${\textstyle 4n-2\log _{2}^{2}(n)-2\log _{2}(n)-4}$ irrational real multiplications are required to compute a DFT of power-of-two length $n=2^{m}$ .
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Moreover, explicit algorithms that achieve this count are known (Heideman & Burrus, 1986; Duhamel, 1990).
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] However, these algorithms require too many additions to be practical, at least on modern computers with hardware multipliers (Duhamel, 1990; Frigo & Johnson, 2005).
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] A tight lower bound is not known on the number of required additions, although lower bounds have been proved under some restrictive assumptions on the algorithms.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] In 1973, Morgenstern proved an $\Omega (n\log n)$ lower bound on the addition count for algorithms where the multiplicative constants have bounded magnitudes (which is true for most but not all FFT algorithms).
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Pan (1986) proved an $\Omega (n\log n)$ lower bound assuming a bound on a measure of the FFT algorithm's *asynchronicity*, but the generality of this assumption is unclear.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] A third problem is to minimize the *total* number of real multiplications and additions, sometimes called the *arithmetic complexity* (although in this context it is the exact count and not the asymptotic complexity that is being considered).
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Again, no tight lower bound has been proven.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Since 1968, however, the lowest published count for power-of-two n was long achieved by the split-radix FFT algorithm, which requires ${\textstyle 4n\log _{2}(n)-6n+8}$ real multiplications and additions for *n* > 1.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] This was further reduced to ${\textstyle \sim {\frac {34}{9}}n\log _{2}n}$ (Johnson and Frigo, 2007; Lundy and Van Buskirk, 2007).
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Most of the attempts to lower or prove the complexity of FFT algorithms have focused on the ordinary complex-data case, because it is the simplest.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] However, complex-data FFTs are so closely related to algorithms for related problems, such as real-data FFTs, discrete cosine transforms, discrete Hartley transforms, and so on, that any improvement in one of these would immediately lead to improvements in the others (Duhamel & Vetterli, 1990).
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] All of the FFT algorithms discussed above compute the DFT exactly (i.e., neglecting floating-point errors).
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] A few FFT algorithms have been proposed, however, that compute the DFT *approximately*, with an error that can be made arbitrarily small at the expense of increased computations.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Such algorithms trade the approximation error for increased speed or other properties.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] For example, an approximate FFT algorithm by Edelman et al.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] (1999) achieves lower communication requirements for parallel computing with the help of a fast multipole method.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] A wavelet-based approximate FFT by Guo and Burrus (1996) takes sparse inputs/outputs (time/frequency localization) into account more efficiently than is possible with an exact FFT.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Another algorithm for approximate computation of a subset of the DFT outputs is due to Shentov et al.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] The Edelman algorithm works equally well for sparse and non-sparse data, since it is based on the compressibility (rank deficiency) of the Fourier matrix itself rather than the compressibility (sparsity) of the data.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] FFT algorithms have errors when finite-precision floating-point arithmetic is used, but these errors are typically quite small; most FFT algorithms, e.g., Cooley–Tukey, have excellent numerical properties as a consequence of the pairwise summation structure of the algorithms.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] The upper bound on the relative error for the Cooley–Tukey algorithm is ${\textstyle O(\varepsilon \log n)}$ , compared to ${\textstyle O(\varepsilon n^{3/2})}$ for the naïve DFT formula, where 𝜀 is the machine floating-point relative precision.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] In fact, the root mean square (rms) errors are much better than these upper bounds, being only ${\textstyle O(\varepsilon {\sqrt {\log n}})}$ for Cooley–Tukey and ${\textstyle O(\varepsilon {\sqrt {n}})}$ for the naïve DFT (Schatzman, 1996).
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] These results, however, are very sensitive to the accuracy of the twiddle factors used in the FFT (i.e. the trigonometric function values), and it is not unusual for incautious FFT implementations to have much worse accuracy, e.g. if they use inaccurate trigonometric recurrence formulas.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Some FFTs other than Cooley–Tukey, such as the Rader–Brenner algorithm, are intrinsically less stable.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] In fixed-point arithmetic, the finite-precision errors accumulated by FFT algorithms are worse, with rms errors growing as ${\textstyle O({\sqrt {n}})}$ for the Cooley–Tukey algorithm (Welch, 1969).
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Achieving this accuracy requires careful attention to scaling to minimize loss of precision, and fixed-point FFT algorithms involve rescaling at each intermediate stage of decompositions like Cooley–Tukey.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] To verify the correctness of an FFT implementation, rigorous guarantees can be obtained in ${\textstyle O(n\log n)}$ time by a simple procedure checking the linearity, impulse-response, and time-shift properties of the transform on random inputs (Ergün, 1995).
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] The values for intermediate frequencies may be obtained by various averaging methods.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Equivalently, it is the composition of a sequence of *d* sets of one-dimensional DFTs, performed along one dimension at a time (in any order).
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] This compositional viewpoint immediately provides the simplest and most common multidimensional DFT algorithm, known as the **row-column** algorithm (after the two-dimensional case, below).
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] That is, one simply performs a sequence of d one-dimensional FFTs (by any of the above algorithms): first you transform along the *n*1 dimension, then along the *n*2 dimension, and so on (actually, any ordering works).
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] This method is easily shown to have the usual ${\textstyle O(n\log n)}$ complexity, where ${\textstyle n=n_{1}\cdot n_{2}\cdots n_{d}}$ is the total number of data points transformed.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] In more than two dimensions, it is often advantageous for cache locality to group the dimensions recursively.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] For example, a three-dimensional FFT might first perform two-dimensional FFTs of each planar slice for each fixed *n*1, and then perform the one-dimensional FFTs along the *n*1 direction.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Still, this remains a straightforward variation of the row-column algorithm that ultimately requires only a one-dimensional FFT algorithm as the base case, and still has $O(n\log n)$ complexity.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Yet another variation is to perform matrix transpositions in between transforming subsequent dimensions, so that the transforms operate on contiguous data; this is especially important for out-of-core and distributed memory situations where accessing non-contiguous data is extremely time-consuming.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] There are other multidimensional FFT algorithms that are distinct from the row-column algorithm, although all of them have ${\textstyle O(n\log n)}$ complexity.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Perhaps the simplest non-row-column FFT is the vector-radix FFT algorithm, which is a generalization of the ordinary Cooley–Tukey algorithm where one divides the transform dimensions by a vector ${\textstyle \mathbf {r} =\left(r_{1},r_{2},\ldots ,r_{d}\right)}$ of radices at each step.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] (This may also have cache benefits.) The simplest case of vector-radix is where all of the radices are equal (e.g., vector-radix-2 divides *all* of the dimensions by two), but this is not necessary.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Vector radix with only a single non-unit radix at a time, i.e. ${\textstyle \mathbf {r} =\left(1,\ldots ,1,r,1,\ldots ,1\right)}$ , is essentially a row-column algorithm.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Other, more complicated, methods include polynomial transform algorithms due to Nussbaumer (1977), which view the transform in terms of convolutions and polynomial products.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] See Duhamel and Vetterli (1990) for more information and references.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] A spherical-harmonic algorithm with ${\textstyle O(n^{2}\log n)}$ complexity is described by Rokhlin and Tygert.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] The fast folding algorithm is analogous to the FFT, except that it operates on a series of binned waveforms rather than a series of real or complex scalar values.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Rotation (which in the FFT is multiplication by a complex phasor) is a circular shift of the component waveform .
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Various groups have also published FFT algorithms for non-equispaced data, as reviewed in Potts *et al.* (2001).
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Such algorithms do not strictly compute the DFT (which is only defined for equispaced data), but rather some approximation thereof (a non-uniform discrete Fourier transform, or NDFT, which itself is often computed only approximately).
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] More generally, there are various other methods of spectral estimation.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] The FFT is used in digital recording, sampling, additive synthesis and pitch correction software.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] The FFT's importance derives from the fact that it has made working in the frequency domain equally computationally feasible as working in the temporal or spatial domain.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] In modern wireless communication standards, the FFT is a critical component for processing signals.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Specifically, it is utilized in Orthogonal frequency-division multiplexing (OFDM) systems, such as 4G LTE and 5G NR.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] The efficiency of the FFT allows for high-speed data transmission by dividing a wideband signal into multiple closely spaced orthogonal subcarriers.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] This technology is essential for reducing interference and optimizing power consumption in mobile devices.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] The FFT can be a poor choice for analyzing signals with non-stationary frequency content—where the frequency characteristics change over time.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] DFTs provide a global frequency estimate, assuming that all frequency components are present throughout the entire signal, which makes it challenging to detect short-lived or transient features within signals.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] For cases where frequency information appears briefly in the signal or generally varies over time, alternatives like the short-time Fourier transform, discrete wavelet transforms, or discrete Hilbert transform can be more suitable.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] These transforms allow for localized frequency analysis by capturing both frequency and time-based information.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] With the explosion of big data in fields such as astronomy, the need for 512K FFTs has arisen for certain interferometry calculations.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] require FFTs of tens of billions of points.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] As this size does not fit into main memory, so-called out-of-core FFTs are an active area of research.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] For applications such as MRI, it is necessary to compute DFTs for nonuniformly spaced grid points and/or frequencies.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Multipole-based approaches can compute approximate quantities with factor of runtime increase.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] A function on any compact group, including non-cyclic, has an expansion in terms of a basis of irreducible matrix elements.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] It remains an active area of research to find an efficient algorithm for performing this change of basis.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] on a quantum computer has a subroutine to compute DFT of a binary vector.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] This is implemented as a sequence of 1- or 2-bit quantum gates now known as quantum FFT, which is effectively the Cooley–Tukey FFT realized as a particular factorization of the Fourier matrix.
[src:dsp/fast-fourier-transform] Extensions to these ideas are currently being explored.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] In signal processing, a **finite impulse response** (**FIR**) **filter** is a filter whose impulse response (or response to any finite length input) is of *finite* duration, because it settles to zero in finite time.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] This is in contrast to infinite impulse response (IIR) filters, which may have internal feedback and may continue to respond indefinitely (usually decaying).
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] The impulse response (that is, the output in response to a Kronecker delta input) of an Nth-order discrete-time FIR filter lasts exactly $N+1$ samples (from first nonzero element through last nonzero element) before it then settles to zero.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] FIR filters can be discrete-time or continuous-time, and digital or analog.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] This computation is also known as discrete convolution.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] The ${\textstyle x[n-i]}$ in these terms are commonly referred to as *taps*, based on the structure of a tapped delay line that in many implementations or block diagrams provides the delayed inputs to the multiplication operations.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] One may speak of a *5th order/6-tap filter*, for instance.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] The impulse response of the filter as defined is nonzero over a finite duration.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] If an FIR filter is non-causal, the range of nonzero values in its impulse response can start before $n=0$ , with the defining formula appropriately generalized.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] An FIR filter has a number of useful properties which sometimes make it preferable to an infinite impulse response (IIR) filter.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] The main disadvantage of FIR filters is that considerably more computation power in a general purpose processor is required compared to an IIR filter with similar sharpness or selectivity, especially when low frequency (relative to the sample rate) cutoffs are needed.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] However, many digital signal processors provide specialized hardware features to make FIR filters approximately as efficient as IIR for many applications.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] where operators ${\mathcal {F}}$ and ${\mathcal {F}}^{-1}$ respectively denote the discrete-time Fourier transform (DTFT) and its inverse.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] Therefore, the complex-valued, multiplicative function $H(\omega )$ is the filter's frequency response.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] where the added subscript denotes $2\pi$ -periodicity.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] Here $\omega$ represents frequency in normalized units (*radians per sample*).
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] The function $H_{2\pi }(2\pi f')$ has a periodicity of 1 with $f'$ in units of *cycles per sample*, which is favored by many filter design applications.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] Conversely, if one wants to design a filter for ordinary frequencies $f_{1},$ $f_{2},$ etc., using an application that expects *cycles per sample*, one would enter $f_{1}/f_{s},$ $f_{2}/f_{s},$ etc.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] FIR filters are designed by finding the coefficients and filter order that meet certain specifications, which can be in the time domain (e.g. a matched filter) or the frequency domain (most common).
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] Matched filters perform a cross-correlation between the input signal and a known pulse shape.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] The FIR convolution is a cross-correlation between the input signal and a time-reversed copy of the impulse response.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] Therefore, the matched filter's impulse response is "designed" by sampling the known pulse-shape and using those samples in reverse order as the coefficients of the filter.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] Parks–McClellan method (also known as the equiripple, optimal, or minimax method).
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] The Remez exchange algorithm is commonly used to find an optimal equiripple set of coefficients.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] Here the user specifies a desired frequency response, a weighting function for errors from this response, and a filter order *N*.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] The algorithm then finds the set of ${\textstyle N+1}$ coefficients that minimize the maximum deviation from the ideal.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] Intuitively, this finds the filter that is as close as possible to the desired response given that only ${\textstyle N+1}$ coefficients can be used.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] This method is particularly easy in practice since at least one text includes a program that takes the desired filter and *N*, and returns the optimum coefficients.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] Equiripple FIR filters can be designed using the DFT algorithms as well.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] The DFT of an initial filter design is computed using the FFT algorithm (if an initial estimate is not available, h[n]=delta[n] can be used).
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] In the Fourier domain, or DFT domain, the frequency response is corrected according to the desired specs, and the inverse DFT is then computed.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] In the time-domain, only the first N coefficients are kept (the other coefficients are set to zero).
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] The process is then repeated iteratively: the DFT is computed once again, correction applied in the frequency domain and so on.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] Software packages such as MATLAB, GNU Octave, Scilab, and SciPy provide convenient ways to apply these different methods.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] In the window design method, one first designs an ideal IIR filter and then truncates the infinite impulse response by multiplying it with a finite length window function.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] The result is a finite impulse response filter whose frequency response is modified from that of the IIR filter.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] Multiplying the infinite impulse by the window function in the time domain results in the frequency response of the IIR being convolved with the Fourier transform (or DTFT) of the window function.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] If the window's main lobe is narrow, the composite frequency response remains close to that of the ideal IIR filter.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] The ideal frequency response is often an ideal, rectangular low-pass, and the corresponding IIR is a sinc function.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] The result of the frequency domain convolution is that the edges of the rectangle are tapered, and ripples appear in the passband and stopband.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] Working backward, one can specify the slope (or width) of the tapered region (*transition band*) and the height of the ripples, and thereby derive the frequency-domain parameters of an appropriate window function.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] Continuing backward to an impulse response can be done by iterating a filter design program to find the minimum filter order.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] Another method is to restrict the solution set to the parametric family of Kaiser windows, which provides closed form relationships between the time-domain and frequency domain parameters.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] In general, that method will not achieve the minimum possible filter order, but it is particularly convenient for automated applications that require dynamic, on-the-fly, filter design.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] The window design method is also advantageous for creating efficient half-band filters, because the corresponding sinc function is zero at every other sample point (except the center one).
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] The product with the window function does not alter the zeros, so almost half of the coefficients of the final impulse response are zero.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] An appropriate implementation of the FIR calculations can exploit that property to double the filter's efficiency.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] To design FIR filter in the MSE sense, we minimize the mean square error between the filter we obtained and the desired filter.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] A moving average filter is a very simple FIR filter.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] It is sometimes called a boxcar filter, especially when followed by decimation, or a sinc-in-frequency.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] The block diagram on the right shows the second-order moving-average filter discussed below.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] The next figure shows the corresponding pole–zero diagram.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] Zero frequency (DC) corresponds to (1, 0), positive frequencies advancing counterclockwise around the circle to the Nyquist frequency at (−1, 0).
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] The magnitude and phase components of ${\textstyle H\left(e^{j\omega }\right)}$ are plotted in the figure.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] But plots like these can also be generated by doing a discrete Fourier transform (DFT) of the impulse response.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] And because of symmetry, filter design or viewing software often displays only the [0, π] region.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] The magnitude plot indicates that the moving-average filter passes low frequencies with a gain near 1 and attenuates high frequencies, and is thus a crude low-pass filter.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] The phase plot is linear except for discontinuities at the two frequencies where the magnitude goes to zero.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] The size of the discontinuities is π, representing a sign reversal.
[src:dsp/finite-impulse-response] They do not affect the property of linear phase, as illustrated in the final figure.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] In practice, the impulse response, even of IIR systems, usually approaches zero and can be neglected past a certain point.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] However the physical systems which give rise to IIR or FIR responses are dissimilar, and therein lies the importance of the distinction.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] For instance, analog electronic filters composed of resistors, capacitors, and/or inductors (and perhaps linear amplifiers) are generally IIR filters.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] On the other hand, discrete-time filters (usually digital filters) based on a tapped delay line *employing no feedback* are necessarily FIR filters.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] The capacitors (or inductors) in the analog filter have a "memory" and their internal state never completely relaxes following an impulse (assuming the classical model of capacitors and inductors where quantum effects are ignored).
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] But in the latter case, after an impulse has reached the end of the tapped delay line, the system has no further memory of that impulse and has returned to its initial state; its impulse response beyond that point is exactly zero.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] Although almost all analog electronic filters are IIR, digital filters may be either IIR or FIR.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] The presence of feedback in the topology of a discrete-time filter (such as the block diagram shown below) generally creates an IIR response.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] The z domain transfer function of an IIR filter contains a non-trivial denominator, describing those feedback terms.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] The transfer function of an FIR filter, on the other hand, has only a numerator as expressed in the general form derived below.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] All of the $a_{i}$ coefficients with $i>0$ (feedback terms) are zero and the filter has no finite poles.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] The transfer functions pertaining to IIR analog electronic filters have been extensively studied and optimized for their amplitude and phase characteristics.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] These continuous-time filter functions are described in the Laplace domain.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] Desired solutions can be transferred to the case of discrete-time filters whose transfer functions are expressed in the z domain, through the use of certain mathematical techniques such as the bilinear transform, impulse invariance, or pole–zero matching method.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] Thus digital IIR filters can be based on well-known solutions for analog filters such as the Chebyshev filter, Butterworth filter, and elliptic filter, inheriting the characteristics of those solutions.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] The transfer function allows one to judge whether or not a system is bounded-input, bounded-output (BIBO) stable.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] To be specific, the BIBO stability criterion requires that the ROC of the system includes the unit circle.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] For example, for a causal system to be stable, all poles of the transfer function have to have an absolute value smaller than one.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] In other words, all poles must be located within a unit circle in the z -plane.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] Clearly, if $a_{j}\neq 0$ then the poles are not located at the origin of the z -plane.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] This is in contrast to the FIR filter where all poles are located at the origin, and is therefore always stable.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] IIR filters are sometimes preferred over FIR filters because an IIR filter can achieve a much sharper transition region roll-off than an FIR filter of the same order.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] governed by the parameter a , a real number with $0<|a|<1$ . $H(z)$ is stable and causal with a pole at a .
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] It can be seen that $h(n)$ is non-zero for all $n\geq 0$ , thus an impulse response which continues infinitely.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] The main advantage digital IIR filters have over FIR filters is their efficiency in implementation, in order to meet a specification in terms of passband, stopband, ripple, and/or roll-off.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] Such a set of specifications can be accomplished with a lower order (*Q* in the above formulae) IIR filter than would be required for an FIR filter meeting the same requirements.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] If implemented in a signal processor, this implies a correspondingly fewer number of calculations per time step; the computational savings is often of a rather large factor.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] On the other hand, FIR filters can be easier to design, for instance, to match a particular frequency response requirement.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] This is particularly true when the requirement is not one of the usual cases (high-pass, low-pass, notch, etc.) which have been studied and optimized for analog filters.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] Also FIR filters can be easily made to be linear phase (constant group delay vs frequency)—a property that is not easily met using IIR filters and then only as an approximation (for instance with the Bessel filter).
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] Another issue regarding digital IIR filters is the potential for limit cycle behavior when idle, due to the feedback system in conjunction with quantization.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] Impulse invariance is a technique for designing discrete-time infinite-impulse-response (IIR) filters from continuous-time filters in which the impulse response of the continuous-time system is sampled to produce the impulse response of the discrete-time system.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] Impulse invariance is one of the commonly used methods to meet the two basic requirements of the mapping from the s-plane to the z-plane.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] This is obtained by solving the T(z) that has the same output value at the same sampling time as the analog filter, and it is only applicable when the inputs are in a pulse.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] Note that all inputs of the digital filter generated by this method are approximate values, except for pulse inputs that are very accurate.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] This is the simplest IIR filter design method.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] It is the most accurate at low frequencies, so it is usually used in low-pass filters.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] For Laplace transform or z-transform, the output after the transformation is just the input multiplied by the corresponding transformation function, T(s) or T(z).
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] Y(s) and Y(z) are the converted output of input X(s) and input X(z), respectively.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] When applying the Laplace transform or z-transform on the unit impulse, the result is 1.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] Now the output of the analog filter is just the inverse Laplace transform in the time domain.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] If we use nT instead of t, we can get the output y(nT) derived from the pulse at the sampling time.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] Pay attention to the fact that there is a multiplier T appearing in the formula.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] This is because even if the Laplace transform and z-transform for the unit pulse are 1, the pulse itself is not necessarily the same.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] For analog signals, the pulse has an infinite value but the area is 1 at t=0, but it is 1 at the discrete-time pulse t=0, so the existence of a multiplier T is required.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] Step invariance is a better design method than impulse invariant.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] The digital filter has several segments of input with different constants when sampling, which is composed of discrete steps.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] The step invariant IIR filter is less accurate than the same input step signal to the ADC.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] However, it is a better approximation for any input than the impulse invariant.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] Step invariant solves the problem of the same sample values when T(z) and T(s) are both step inputs.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] The input to the digital filter is u(n), and the input to the analog filter is u(t).
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] Apply z-transform and Laplace transform on these two inputs to obtain the converted output signal.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] If sampled every T seconds, it is y(n), which is the inverse conversion of Y(z).These signals are used to solve for the digital filter and the analog filter and have the same output at the sampling time.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] The following equation points out the solution of T(z), which is the approximate formula for the analog filter.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] The bilinear transform is a first-order approximation of the natural logarithm function that is an exact mapping of the *z*-plane to the *s*-plane.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] where T is the numerical integration step size of the trapezoidal rule used in the bilinear transform derivation; or, in other words, the sampling period.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] The above bilinear approximation can be solved for s or a similar approximation for $s=(1/T)\ln(z)$ can be performed.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] This relationship is used in the Laplace transfer function of any analog filter or the digital infinite impulse response (IIR) filter T(z) of the analog filter.
[src:dsp/infinite-impulse-response] which is used to calculate the IIR digital filter, starting from the Laplace transfer function of the analog filter.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] The **Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem** is a theorem in the field of signal processing which serves as a fundamental bridge between continuous-time signals and discrete-time signals.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Strictly speaking, the theorem only applies to a class of mathematical functions having a Fourier transform that is zero outside of a finite region of frequencies.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Intuitively we expect that when one reduces a continuous function to a discrete sequence and interpolates back to a continuous function, the fidelity of the result depends on the density (or sample rate) of the original samples.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] The sampling theorem introduces the concept of a sample rate that is sufficient for perfect fidelity for the class of functions that are band-limited to a given bandwidth, such that no actual information is lost in the sampling process.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] It expresses the sufficient sample rate in terms of the bandwidth for the class of functions.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] The theorem also leads to a formula for perfectly reconstructing the original continuous-time function from the samples.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Perfect reconstruction may still be possible when the sample-rate criterion is not satisfied, provided other constraints on the signal are known (see § Sampling of non-baseband signals below and compressed sensing).
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] In some cases (when the sample-rate criterion is not satisfied), utilizing additional constraints allows for approximate reconstructions.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] The fidelity of these reconstructions can be verified and quantified utilizing Bochner's theorem.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] An important consequence of the sampling theorem is the concept of Nyquist frequency, which holds that in order to reconstruct a bandlimited signal free of aliasing, the sampling rate must be at least twice the signal's bandwidth.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] The name *Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem* honours Harry Nyquist and Claude Shannon, but the theorem was also previously discovered by E.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Whittaker (published in 1915), and Shannon cited Whittaker's paper in his work.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] The theorem is thus also known by the names *Whittaker–Shannon sampling theorem*, *Whittaker–Shannon*, and *Whittaker–Nyquist–Shannon*, and may also be referred to as the *cardinal theorem of interpolation*.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Sampling is a process of converting a signal (for example, a function of continuous time or space) into a sequence of values (a function of discrete time or space).
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] A sufficient sample-rate is therefore anything larger than $2B$ samples per second.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Equivalently, for a given sample rate $f_{s}$ , perfect reconstruction is guaranteed possible for a bandlimit $B<f_{s}/2$ .
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] When the bandlimit is too high (or there is no bandlimit), the reconstruction exhibits imperfections known as aliasing.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Modern statements of the theorem are sometimes careful to explicitly state that $x(t)$ must contain no sinusoidal component at exactly frequency $B,$ or that B must be strictly less than one half the sample rate.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] The threshold $2B$ is called the Nyquist rate and is an attribute of the continuous-time input $x(t)$ to be sampled.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] The sample rate must exceed the Nyquist rate for the samples to suffice to represent $x(t).$ The threshold $f_{s}/2$ is called the Nyquist frequency and is an attribute of the sampling equipment.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] All meaningful frequency components of the properly sampled $x(t)$ exist below the Nyquist frequency.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] The condition described by these inequalities is called the *Nyquist criterion*, or sometimes the *Raabe condition*.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] The theorem is also applicable to functions of other domains, such as space, in the case of a digitized image.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] The symbol $T\triangleq 1/f_{s}$ is customarily used to represent the interval between adjacent samples and is called the *sample period* or *sampling interval*.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] A mathematically ideal way to interpolate the sequence involves the use of sinc functions.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Each sample in the sequence is replaced by a sinc function, centered on the time axis at the original location of the sample $nT,$ with the amplitude of the sinc function scaled to the sample value, $x(nT).$ Subsequently, the sinc functions are summed into a continuous function.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] A mathematically equivalent method uses the Dirac comb and proceeds by convolving one sinc function with a series of Dirac delta pulses, weighted by the sample values.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Neither method is numerically practical.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Instead, some type of approximation of the sinc functions, finite in length, is used.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] The imperfections attributable to the approximation are known as *interpolation error*.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Practical digital-to-analog converters produce neither scaled and delayed sinc functions, nor ideal Dirac pulses.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Instead they produce a piecewise-constant sequence of scaled and delayed rectangular pulses (the zero-order hold), usually followed by a lowpass filter (called an "anti-imaging filter") to remove spurious high-frequency replicas (images) of the original baseband signal.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] which is a periodic function and its equivalent representation as a Fourier series, whose coefficients are $x[n]$ .
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] This function is also known as the discrete-time Fourier transform (DTFT) of the sample sequence.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] As depicted, copies of $X(f)$ are shifted by multiples of the sampling rate $f_{s}=1/T$ and combined by addition.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] For a band-limited function $(X(f)=0,{\text{ for all }}|f|\geq B)$ and sufficiently large $f_{s},$ it is possible for the copies to remain distinct from each other.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] But if the Nyquist criterion is not satisfied, adjacent copies overlap, and it is not possible in general to discern an unambiguous $X(f).$ Any frequency component above $f_{s}/2$ is indistinguishable from a lower-frequency component, called an *alias*, associated with one of the copies.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] In such cases, the customary interpolation techniques produce the alias, rather than the original component.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] When the sample-rate is pre-determined by other considerations (such as an industry standard), $x(t)$ is usually filtered to reduce its high frequencies to acceptable levels before it is sampled.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] The type of filter required is a lowpass filter, and in this application it is called an anti-aliasing filter.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] The sampling theorem is proved since $X(f)$ uniquely determines $x(t)$ .
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] All that remains is to derive the formula for reconstruction. $H(f)$ need not be precisely defined in the region $[B,\ f_{s}-B]$ because $X_{1/T}(f)$ is zero in that region.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] However, the worst case is when $B=f_{s}/2,$ the Nyquist frequency.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] where $\mathrm {rect}$ is the rectangular function.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] which shows how the samples, $x(nT)$ , can be combined to reconstruct $x(t)$ .
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Poisson shows that the Fourier series in **Eq.1** produces the periodic summation of $X(f)$ , regardless of $f_{s}$ and B .
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Shannon, however, only derives the series coefficients for the case $f_{s}=2B$ .
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] is determined if its Fourier coefficients are determined.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] completely, since a function is determined if its spectrum is known.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] Shannon's proof of the theorem is complete at that point, but he goes on to discuss reconstruction via sinc functions, what we now call the Whittaker–Shannon interpolation formula as discussed above.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] He does not derive or prove the properties of the sinc function, as the Fourier pair relationship between the rect (the rectangular function) and sinc functions was well known by that time.
[src:dsp/nyquist-shannon-sampling-theorem] As in the other proof, the existence of the Fourier transform of the original signal is assumed, so the proof does not say whether the sampling theorem extends to bandlimited stationary random processes.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] In mathematics and digital signal processing, **quantization** is the process of mapping input values from a large set (often a continuous set) to output values in a (countable) smaller set, often with a finite number of elements.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Rounding and truncation are typical examples of quantization processes.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization is involved to some degree in nearly all digital signal processing, as the process of representing a signal in digital form ordinarily involves rounding.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization also forms the core of essentially all lossy compression algorithms.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] The difference between an input value and its quantized value (such as round-off error) is referred to as **quantization error**, **noise** or **distortion**.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] A device or algorithmic function that performs quantization is called a **quantizer**.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] An analog-to-digital converter is an example of a quantizer.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] For example, rounding a real number x to the nearest integer value forms a very basic type of quantizer – a *uniform* one.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] where the notation $\lfloor \ \rfloor$ denotes the floor function.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] (The notation $\lceil \ \rceil$ denotes the ceiling function).
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] The essential property of a quantizer is having a countable set of possible output values smaller than the set of possible input values.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] The members of the set of output values may have integer, rational, or real values.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] For simple rounding to the nearest integer, the step size $\Delta$ is equal to 1.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] With $\Delta =1$ or with $\Delta$ equal to any other integer value, this quantizer has real-valued inputs and integer-valued outputs.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] When the quantization step size (Δ) is small relative to the variation in the signal being quantized, it is relatively simple to show that the mean squared error produced by such a rounding operation will be approximately $\Delta ^{2}/12$ .
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Mean squared error is also called the quantization *noise power*.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Adding one bit to the quantizer halves the value of Δ, which reduces the noise power by the factor ⁠1/4⁠.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] This two-stage decomposition applies equally well to vector as well as scalar quantizers.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Because quantization is a many-to-few mapping, it is an inherently non-linear and irreversible process (i.e., because the same output value is shared by multiple input values, it is impossible, in general, to recover the exact input value when given only the output value).
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] The set of possible input values may be infinitely large, and may possibly be continuous and therefore uncountable (such as the set of all real numbers, or all real numbers within some limited range).
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] The set of possible output values may be finite or countably infinite.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] The input and output sets involved in quantization can be defined in a rather general way.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] For example, vector quantization is the application of quantization to multi-dimensional (vector-valued) input data.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] An analog-to-digital converter (ADC) can be modeled as two processes: sampling and quantization.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Sampling converts a time-varying voltage signal into a discrete-time signal, a sequence of real numbers.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization replaces each real number with an approximation from a finite set of discrete values.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Most commonly, these discrete values are represented as fixed-point words.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Though any number of quantization levels is possible, common word lengths are 8-bit (256 levels), 16-bit (65,536 levels) and 24-bit (16.8 million levels).
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Quantizing a sequence of numbers produces a sequence of quantization errors, which is sometimes modeled as an additive random signal called **quantization noise** because of its stochastic behavior.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] The more levels a quantizer uses, the lower is its quantization noise power.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Most uniform quantizers for signed input data can be classified as being of one of two types: *mid-riser* and *mid-tread*.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] The terminology is based on what happens in the region around the value 0, and uses the analogy of viewing the input-output function of the quantizer as a stairway.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Mid-tread quantizers have a zero-valued reconstruction level (corresponding to a *tread* of a stairway), while mid-riser quantizers have a zero-valued classification threshold (corresponding to a *riser* of a stairway).
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Mid-tread quantization involves rounding.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] The formulas for mid-tread uniform quantization are provided in the previous section.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Mid-riser quantization involves truncation.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Note that mid-riser uniform quantizers do not have a zero output value – their minimum output magnitude is half the step size.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] In contrast, mid-tread quantizers do have a zero output level.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] For some applications, having a zero output signal representation may be a necessity.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] In general, a mid-riser or mid-tread quantizer may not actually be a *uniform* quantizer – i.e., the size of the quantizer's classification intervals may not all be the same, or the spacing between its possible output values may not all be the same.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] The distinguishing characteristic of a mid-riser quantizer is that it has a classification threshold value that is exactly zero, and the distinguishing characteristic of a mid-tread quantizer is that is it has a reconstruction value that is exactly zero.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] A **dead-zone quantizer** is a type of mid-tread quantizer with symmetric behavior around 0.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] The region around the zero output value of such a quantizer is referred to as the *dead zone* or *deadband*.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] The dead zone can sometimes serve the same purpose as a noise gate or squelch function.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Especially for compression applications, the dead-zone may be given a different width than that for the other steps.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] where the function $\operatorname {sgn}$ ( ) is the sign function (also known as the *signum* function).
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] where $r_{k}$ is a reconstruction offset value in the range of 0 to 1 as a fraction of the step size.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Ordinarily, $0\leq r_{k}\leq {\tfrac {1}{2}}$ when quantizing input data with a typical probability density function (PDF) that is symmetric around zero and reaches its peak value at zero (such as a Gaussian, Laplacian, or generalized Gaussian PDF).
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Although $r_{k}$ may depend on k in general and can be chosen to fulfill the optimality condition described below, it is often simply set to a constant, such as ${\tfrac {1}{2}}$ .
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] A very commonly used special case (e.g., the scheme typically used in financial accounting and elementary mathematics) is to set $w=\Delta$ and $r_{k}={\tfrac {1}{2}}$ for all k .
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] In this case, the dead-zone quantizer is also a uniform quantizer, since the central dead-zone of this quantizer has the same width as all of its other steps, and all of its reconstruction values are equally spaced as well.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] A common assumption for the analysis of quantization error is that it affects a signal processing system in a similar manner to that of additive white noise – having negligible correlation with the signal and an approximately flat power spectral density.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] The additive noise model is commonly used for the analysis of quantization error effects in digital filtering systems, and it can be very useful in such analysis.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] It has been shown to be a valid model in cases of high-resolution quantization (small $\Delta$ relative to the signal strength) with smooth PDFs.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Additive noise behavior is not always a valid assumption.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization error (for quantizers defined as described here) is deterministically related to the signal and not entirely independent of it.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Thus, periodic signals can create periodic quantization noise.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] And in some cases, it can even cause limit cycles to appear in digital signal processing systems.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] One way to ensure effective independence of the quantization error from the source signal is to perform *dithered quantization* (sometimes with *noise shaping*), which involves adding random (or pseudo-random) noise to the signal prior to quantization.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] In the typical case, the original signal is much larger than one least significant bit (LSB).
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] When this is the case, the quantization error is not significantly correlated with the signal and has an approximately uniform distribution.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] When rounding is used to quantize, the quantization error has a mean of zero and the root mean square (RMS) value is the standard deviation of this distribution, given by $\scriptstyle {\frac {1}{\sqrt {12}}}\mathrm {LSB} \ \approx \ 0.289\,\mathrm {LSB}$ .
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] When truncation is used, the error has a non-zero mean of $\scriptstyle {\frac {1}{2}}\mathrm {LSB}$ and the RMS value is $\scriptstyle {\frac {1}{\sqrt {3}}}\mathrm {LSB}$ .
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Although rounding yields less RMS error than truncation, the difference is only due to the static (DC) term of $\scriptstyle {\frac {1}{2}}\mathrm {LSB}$ .
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] The RMS values of the AC error are exactly the same in both cases, so there is no special advantage of rounding over truncation in situations where the DC term of the error can be ignored (such as in AC-coupled systems).
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] In either case, the standard deviation, as a percentage of the full signal range, changes by a factor of 2 for each 1-bit change in the number of quantization bits.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] The potential signal-to-quantization-noise power ratio therefore changes by 4, or $\scriptstyle 10\cdot \log _{10}(4)$ , approximately 6 dB per bit.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] At lower amplitudes, the quantization error becomes dependent on the input signal, resulting in distortion.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] This distortion is created after the anti-aliasing filter, and if these distortions are above 1/2 the sample rate, they will alias back into the band of interest.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] In order to make the quantization error independent of the input signal, the signal is dithered by adding noise to the signal.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] This slightly reduces signal-to-noise ratio, but can completely eliminate the distortion.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization noise is a model of quantization error introduced by quantization in the ADC.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] It is a rounding error between the analog input voltage to the ADC and the output digitized value.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] The noise is non-linear and signal-dependent.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] It can be modeled in several different ways.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] where Q is the number of quantization bits.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] The most common test signals that fulfill this are full amplitude triangle waves and sawtooth waves.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] For example, a 16-bit ADC has a maximum signal-to-quantization-noise ratio of 6.02 × 16 = 96.3 dB.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Here, the quantization noise is once again *assumed* to be uniformly distributed.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] When the input signal has a high amplitude and a wide frequency spectrum, this is the case.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] In this case a 16-bit ADC has a maximum signal-to-noise ratio of 98.09 dB.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] The 1.761 difference in signal-to-noise only occurs due to the signal being a full-scale sine wave instead of a triangle or sawtooth.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] For complex signals in high-resolution ADCs this is an accurate model.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] For low-resolution ADCs, low-level signals in high-resolution ADCs, and for simple waveforms the quantization noise is not uniformly distributed, making this model inaccurate.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] In these cases the quantization noise distribution is strongly affected by the exact amplitude of the signal.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] The calculations are relative to full-scale input.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] For smaller signals, the relative quantization distortion can be very large.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] To circumvent this issue, analog companding can be used, but this can introduce distortion.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Often, the design of a quantizer involves supporting only a limited range of possible output values and performing clipping to limit the output to this range whenever the input exceeds the supported range.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] The error introduced by this clipping is referred to as *overload* distortion.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Within the extreme limits of the supported range, the amount of spacing between the selectable output values of a quantizer is referred to as its *granularity*, and the error introduced by this spacing is referred to as *granular* distortion.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] It is common for the design of a quantizer to involve determining the proper balance between granular distortion and overload distortion.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] For a given supported number of possible output values, reducing the average granular distortion may involve increasing the average overload distortion, and vice versa.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] A technique for controlling the amplitude of the signal (or, equivalently, the quantization step size $\Delta$ ) to achieve the appropriate balance is the use of *automatic gain control* (AGC).
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] However, in some quantizer designs, the concepts of granular error and overload error may not apply (e.g., for a quantizer with a limited range of input data or with a countably infinite set of selectable output values).
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] These two stages together comprise the mathematical operation of $y=Q(x)$ .
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Entropy coding techniques can be applied to communicate the quantization indices from a source encoder that performs the classification stage to a decoder that performs the reconstruction stage.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] One way to do this is to associate each quantization index k with a binary codeword $c_{k}$ .
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] An important consideration is the number of bits used for each codeword, denoted here by $\mathrm {length} (c_{k})$ .
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] A key observation is that rate R depends on the decision boundaries $\{b_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M-1}$ and the codeword lengths $\{\mathrm {length} (c_{k})\}_{k=1}^{M}$ , whereas the distortion D depends on the decision boundaries $\{b_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M-1}$ and the reconstruction levels $\{y_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M}$ .
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Solving the unconstrained problem is equivalent to finding a point on the convex hull of the family of solutions to an equivalent constrained formulation of the problem.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] However, finding a solution – especially a closed-form solution – to any of these three problem formulations can be difficult.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Solutions that do not require multi-dimensional iterative optimization techniques have been published for only three PDFs: the uniform, exponential, and Laplacian distributions.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Iterative optimization approaches can be used to find solutions in other cases.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] This observation can be used to ease the analysis – given the set of $\{b_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M-1}$ values, the value of each $y_{k}$ can be optimized separately to minimize its contribution to the distortion D .
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] The use of this approximation can allow the entropy coding design problem to be separated from the design of the quantizer itself.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Modern entropy coding techniques such as arithmetic coding can achieve bit rates that are very close to the true entropy of a source, given a set of known (or adaptively estimated) probabilities $\{p_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M}$ .
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] In some designs, rather than optimizing for a particular number of classification regions M , the quantizer design problem may include optimization of the value of M as well.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] For some probabilistic source models, the best performance may be achieved when M approaches infinity.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] The indices produced by an M -level quantizer can be coded using a fixed-length code using $R=\lceil \log _{2}M\rceil$ bits/symbol.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] For example, when $M=$ 256 levels, the FLC bit rate R is 8 bits/symbol.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] For this reason, such a quantizer has sometimes been called an 8-bit quantizer.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] However, using an FLC eliminates the compression improvement that can be obtained by use of better entropy coding.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Assuming an FLC with M levels, the rate–distortion minimization problem can be reduced to distortion minimization alone.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] which places each reconstruction value at the centroid (conditional expected value) of its associated classification interval.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Lloyd's Method I algorithm, originally described in 1957, can be generalized in a straightforward way for application to vector data.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] This generalization results in the Linde–Buzo–Gray (LBG) or k-means classifier optimization methods.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Moreover, the technique can be further generalized in a straightforward way to also include an entropy constraint for vector data.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] The Lloyd–Max quantizer is actually a uniform quantizer when the input PDF is uniformly distributed over the range $[y_{1}-\Delta /2,~y_{M}+\Delta /2)$ .
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] However, for a source that does not have a uniform distribution, the minimum-distortion quantizer may not be a uniform quantizer.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] The property of 6 dB improvement in SQNR for each extra bit used in quantization is a well-known figure of merit.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] However, it must be used with care: this derivation is only for a uniform quantizer applied to a uniform source.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] For other source PDFs and other quantizer designs, the SQNR may be somewhat different from that predicted by 6 dB/bit, depending on the type of PDF, the type of source, the type of quantizer, and the bit rate range of operation.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] However, it is common to assume that for many sources, the slope of a quantizer SQNR function can be approximated as 6 dB/bit when operating at a sufficiently high bit rate.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] At asymptotically high bit rates, the 6 dB/bit approximation is supported for many source PDFs by rigorous theoretical analysis.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Moreover, the structure of the optimal scalar quantizer (in the rate–distortion sense) approaches that of a uniform quantizer under these conditions.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Many physical quantities are actually quantized by physical entities.
[src:dsp/quantization-signal-processing] Examples of fields where this limitation applies include electronics (due to electrons), optics (due to photons), biology (due to DNA), physics (due to Planck limits) and chemistry (due to molecules).
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] In signal processing, **sampling** is the reduction of a continuous-time signal to a discrete-time signal.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] A common example is the conversion of a sound wave to a sequence of "samples".
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] A **sample** is a value of the signal at a point in time and/or space; this definition differs from the term's usage in statistics, which refers to a set of such values.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] A **sampler** is a subsystem or operation that extracts samples from a continuous signal.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] A theoretical **ideal sampler** produces samples equivalent to the instantaneous value of the continuous signal at the desired points.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] The original signal can be reconstructed from a sequence of samples, up to the Nyquist limit, by passing the sequence of samples through a reconstruction filter.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] Functions of space, time, or any other dimension can be sampled, and similarly in two or more dimensions.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] For functions that vary with time, let $s(t)$ be a continuous function (or "signal") to be sampled, and let sampling be performed by measuring the value of the continuous function every T seconds, which is called the **sampling interval** or **sampling period**.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] The **sampling frequency** or **sampling rate**, $f_{s}$ , is the average number of samples obtained in one second, thus $f_{s}=1/T$ , with the unit *samples per second*, sometimes referred to as hertz, for example 48 kHz is 48,000 *samples per second*.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] Reconstructing a continuous function from samples is done by interpolation algorithms.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] The Whittaker–Shannon interpolation formula is mathematically equivalent to an ideal low-pass filter whose input is a sequence of Dirac delta functions that are modulated (multiplied) by the sample values.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] When the time interval between adjacent samples is a constant $(T)$ , the sequence of delta functions is called a Dirac comb.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] Mathematically, the modulated Dirac comb is equivalent to the product of the comb function with $s(t)$ .
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] That mathematical abstraction is sometimes referred to as *impulse sampling*.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] The fidelity of a theoretical reconstruction is a common measure of the effectiveness of sampling.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] That fidelity is reduced when $s(t)$ contains frequency components whose cycle length (period) is less than 2 sample intervals (see *Aliasing*).
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] The corresponding frequency limit, in *cycles per second* (hertz), is $0.5$ cycle/sample × $f_{s}$ samples/second = $f_{s}/2$ , known as the Nyquist frequency of the sampler.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] Therefore, $s(t)$ is usually the output of a low-pass filter, functionally known as an *anti-aliasing filter*.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] Without an anti-aliasing filter, frequencies higher than the Nyquist frequency will influence the samples in a way that is misinterpreted by the interpolation process.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] In practice, the continuous signal is sampled using an analog-to-digital converter (ADC), a device with various physical limitations.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] This results in deviations from the theoretically perfect reconstruction, collectively referred to as distortion.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] Although the use of oversampling can completely eliminate aperture error and aliasing by shifting them out of the passband, this technique cannot be practically used above a few GHz, and may be prohibitively expensive at much lower frequencies.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] Furthermore, while oversampling can reduce quantization error and non-linearity, it cannot eliminate these entirely.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] Consequently, practical ADCs at audio frequencies typically do not exhibit aliasing or aperture error, and are not limited by quantization error.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] At RF and microwave frequencies, where oversampling is impractical and filters are expensive, aperture error, quantization error and aliasing can be significant limitations.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] Jitter, noise, and quantization are often analyzed by modeling them as random errors added to the sample values.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] Integration and zero-order hold effects can be analyzed as a form of low-pass filtering.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] The non-linearities of either ADC or DAC are analyzed by replacing the ideal linear function mapping with a proposed nonlinear function.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] Digital audio systems typically employ pulse-code modulation (PCM) to encode sound as a series of discrete samples of the electrical level of an analog audio signal.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] Analog signals are captured (encoded) as PCM samples in analog-to-digital conversion (ADC), and reproduced (decoded) using digital-to-analog conversion (DAC).
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] The encoding used for the storage and transmission of digitised sound data within the system may differ.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] When it is necessary to capture audio covering the entire 20–20,000 Hz range of human hearing such as when recording music or many types of acoustic events, audio waveforms are typically sampled at 44.1 kHz (CD), 48 kHz, 88.2 kHz, or 96 kHz.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] The approximately double-rate requirement is a consequence of the Nyquist theorem.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] Sampling rates higher than about 50 kHz to 60 kHz cannot supply more usable information for human listeners.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] Early professional audio equipment manufacturers chose sampling rates in the region of 40 to 50 kHz for this reason.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] Conversely, ultrasonic sounds may interact with and modulate the audible part of the frequency spectrum (intermodulation distortion), *degrading* the fidelity.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] One advantage of higher sampling rates is that they can relax the low-pass filter design requirements for ADCs and DACs, but with modern oversampling delta-sigma-converters, this advantage is less important.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] The Audio Engineering Society recommends 48 kHz sampling rate for most applications, but gives recognition to 44.1 kHz for CD and other consumer uses, 32 kHz for transmission-related applications, and 96 kHz for higher bandwidth or relaxed anti-aliasing filtering.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] Robert Stuart state that the ideal sampling rate would be about 60 kHz, but since this is not a standard frequency, recommend 88.2 or 96 kHz for recording purposes.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] Audio is typically recorded at 8-, 16-, and 24-bit depth; which yield a theoretical maximum signal-to-quantization-noise ratio (SQNR) for a pure sine wave of, approximately; 49.93 dB, 98.09 dB, and 122.17 dB.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] Thermal noise limits the true number of bits that can be used in quantization.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] Few analog systems have signal to noise ratios (SNR) exceeding 120 dB.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] However, digital signal processing operations can have very high dynamic range, consequently, it is common to perform mixing and mastering operations at 32-bit floating-point precision and then convert to 16- or 24-bit for distribution.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] Speech signals, i.e., signals intended to carry only human speech, can usually be sampled at a much lower rate.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] For most phonemes, almost all of the energy is contained in the 100 Hz – 4 kHz range, allowing a sampling rate of 8 kHz.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] This is the sampling rate used by nearly all telephony systems, which use the G.711 sampling and quantization specifications.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] Standard-definition television (SDTV) uses either 720 by 480 pixels (US NTSC 525-line) or 720 by 576 pixels (UK PAL 625-line) for the visible picture area.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] High-definition television (HDTV) uses 720p (progressive), 1080i (interlaced), and 1080p (progressive, also known as Full-HD).
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] In digital video, the temporal sampling rate is defined as the frame rate – or rather the field rate – rather than the notional pixel clock.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] The image sampling frequency is the repetition rate of the sensor integration period.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] Video digital-to-analog converters operate in the megahertz range (from ~3 MHz for low-quality composite video scalers in early game consoles, to 250 MHz or more for the highest-resolution VGA output).
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] When analog video is converted to digital video, a different sampling process occurs, this time at the pixel frequency, corresponding to a spatial sampling rate along scan lines.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] Spatial sampling in the other direction is determined by the spacing of scan lines in the raster.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] The sampling rates and resolutions in both spatial directions can be measured in units of lines per picture height.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] Spatial aliasing of high-frequency luma or chroma video components shows up as a moiré pattern.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] The process of volume rendering samples a 3D grid of voxels to produce 3D renderings of sliced (tomographic) data.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] The 3D grid is assumed to represent a continuous region of 3D space.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] Volume rendering is common in medical imaging, X-ray computed tomography (CT/CAT), magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), positron emission tomography (PET) are some examples.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] It is also used for seismic tomography and other applications.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] When a bandpass signal is sampled slower than its Nyquist rate, the samples are indistinguishable from samples of a low-frequency alias of the high-frequency signal.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] That is often done purposefully in such a way that the lowest-frequency alias satisfies the Nyquist criterion, because the bandpass signal is still uniquely represented and recoverable.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] Oversampling is used in most modern analog-to-digital converters to reduce the distortion introduced by practical digital-to-analog converters, such as a zero-order hold instead of idealizations like the Whittaker–Shannon interpolation formula.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] Although complex-valued samples can be obtained as described above, they are also created by manipulating samples of a real-valued waveform.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] For instance, the equivalent baseband waveform can be created without explicitly computing ${\hat {s}}(t)$ , by processing the product sequence, $\left[s(nT)\cdot e^{-i2\pi {\frac {B}{2}}Tn}\right]$ , through a digital low-pass filter whose cutoff frequency is $B/2$ .
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] Computing only every other sample of the output sequence reduces the sample rate commensurate with the reduced Nyquist rate.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] The result is half as many complex-valued samples as the original number of real samples.
[src:dsp/sampling-signal-processing] No information is lost, and the original $s(t)$ waveform can be recovered, if necessary.
[src:dsp/window-function] In signal processing and statistics, a **window function** (also known as an **apodization function** or **tapering function**) is a mathematical function that is zero-valued outside of some chosen interval.
[src:dsp/window-function] Typically, window functions are symmetric around the middle of the interval, approach a maximum in the middle, and taper away from the middle.
[src:dsp/window-function] Mathematically, when another function or waveform/data-sequence is "multiplied" by a window function, the product is also zero-valued outside the interval: all that is left is the part where they overlap, the "view through the window".
[src:dsp/window-function] Equivalently, and in actual practice, the segment of data within the window is first isolated, and then only that data is multiplied by the window function values.
[src:dsp/window-function] Thus, tapering, not segmentation, is the main purpose of window functions.
[src:dsp/window-function] The reasons for examining segments of a longer function include detection of transient events and time-averaging of frequency spectra.
[src:dsp/window-function] The duration of the segments is determined in each application by requirements like time and frequency resolution.
[src:dsp/window-function] But that method also changes the frequency content of the signal by an effect called spectral leakage.
[src:dsp/window-function] Window functions allow us to distribute the leakage spectrally in different ways, according to the needs of the particular application.
[src:dsp/window-function] There are many choices detailed in this article, but many of the differences are so subtle as to be insignificant in practice.
[src:dsp/window-function] In typical applications, the window functions used are non-negative, smooth, "bell-shaped" curves.
[src:dsp/window-function] Rectangle, triangle, and other functions can also be used.
[src:dsp/window-function] A more general definition of window functions does not require them to be identically zero outside an interval, as long as the product of the window multiplied by its argument is square integrable, and, more specifically, that the function goes sufficiently rapidly toward zero.
[src:dsp/window-function] Window functions are used in spectral analysis/modification/resynthesis, the design of finite impulse response filters, merging multiscale and multidimensional datasets, as well as beamforming and antenna design.
[src:dsp/window-function] The Fourier transform of the function cos(*ωt*) is zero, except at frequency ±*ω*.
[src:dsp/window-function] However, many other functions and waveforms do not have convenient closed-form transforms.
[src:dsp/window-function] Alternatively, one might be interested in their spectral content only during a certain time period.
[src:dsp/window-function] In either case, the Fourier transform (or a similar transform) can be applied on one or more finite intervals of the waveform.
[src:dsp/window-function] In general, the transform is applied to the product of the waveform and a window function.
[src:dsp/window-function] Any window (including rectangular) affects the spectral estimate computed by this method.
[src:dsp/window-function] Windows are sometimes used in the design of digital filters, in particular to convert an "ideal" impulse response of infinite duration, such as a sinc function, to a finite impulse response (FIR) filter design.
[src:dsp/window-function] Window functions are sometimes used in the field of statistical analysis to restrict the set of data being analyzed to a range near a given point, with a weighting factor that diminishes the effect of points farther away from the portion of the curve being fit.
[src:dsp/window-function] In the field of Bayesian analysis and curve fitting, this is often referred to as the kernel.
[src:dsp/window-function] When analyzing a transient signal in modal analysis, such as an impulse, a shock response, a sine burst, a chirp burst, or noise burst, where the energy vs time distribution is extremely uneven, the rectangular window may be most appropriate.
[src:dsp/window-function] For instance, when most of the energy is located at the beginning of the recording, a non-rectangular window attenuates most of the energy, degrading the signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:dsp/window-function] One might wish to measure the harmonic content of a musical note from a particular instrument or the harmonic distortion of an amplifier at a given frequency.
[src:dsp/window-function] Referring again to **Figure 2**, we can observe that there is no leakage at a discrete set of harmonically-related frequencies sampled by the discrete Fourier transform (DFT).
[src:dsp/window-function] (The spectral nulls are actually zero-crossings, which cannot be shown on a logarithmic scale such as this.) This property is unique to the rectangular window, and it must be appropriately configured for the signal frequency, as described above.
[src:dsp/window-function] When the length of a data set to be transformed is larger than necessary to provide the desired frequency resolution, a common practice is to subdivide it into smaller sets and window them individually.
[src:dsp/window-function] To mitigate the "loss" at the edges of the window, the individual sets may overlap in time.
[src:dsp/window-function] See Welch method of power spectral analysis and the modified discrete cosine transform.
[src:dsp/window-function] Two-dimensional windows are commonly used in image processing to reduce unwanted high-frequencies in the image Fourier transform.
[src:dsp/window-function] They can be constructed from one-dimensional windows in either of two forms.
[src:dsp/window-function] The separable form, $W(m,n)=w(m)w(n)$ is trivial to compute.
[src:dsp/window-function] The radial form, $W(m,n)=w(r)$ , which involves the radius $r={\sqrt {(m-M/2)^{2}+(n-N/2)^{2}}}$ , is isotropic, independent on the orientation of the coordinate axes.
[src:dsp/window-function] Only the Gaussian function is both separable and isotropic.
[src:dsp/window-function] The separable forms of all other window functions have corners that depend on the choice of the coordinate axes.
[src:dsp/window-function] The isotropy/anisotropy of a two-dimensional window function is shared by its two-dimensional Fourier transform.
[src:dsp/window-function] The difference between the separable and radial forms is akin to the result of diffraction from rectangular vs. circular apertures, which can be visualized in terms of the product of two sinc functions vs. an Airy function, respectively.
[src:dsp/window-function] The sparse sampling of a discrete-time Fourier transform (DTFT) such as the DFTs in Fig 2 only reveals the leakage into the DFT bins from a sinusoid whose frequency is also an integer DFT bin.
[src:dsp/window-function] The unseen sidelobes reveal the leakage to expect from sinusoids at other frequencies.
[src:dsp/window-function] Therefore, when choosing a window function, it is usually important to sample the DTFT more densely (as we do throughout this section) and choose a window that suppresses the sidelobes to an acceptable level.
[src:dsp/window-function] Other windows are designed to moderate these sudden changes, to reduce scalloping loss and improve dynamic range (described in § Spectral analysis).
[src:dsp/window-function] The rectangular window is the 1st-order *B*-spline window as well as the 0th-power power-of-sine window.
[src:dsp/window-function] The rectangular window provides the minimum mean square error estimate of the Discrete-time Fourier transform, at the cost of other issues discussed.
[src:dsp/window-function] The first one is also known as **Bartlett window** or **Fejér window**.
[src:dsp/window-function] All three definitions converge at large *N*.
[src:dsp/window-function] The triangular window is the 2nd-order *B*-spline window.
[src:dsp/window-function] The *L* = *N* form can be seen as the convolution of two N⁄2-width rectangular windows.
[src:dsp/window-function] The Fourier transform of the result is the squared values of the transform of the half-width rectangular window.
[src:dsp/window-function] The defining quadratic polynomial reaches a value of zero at the samples just outside the span of the window.
[src:dsp/window-function] The Welch window is fairly close to the sine window, and just as the power-of-sine windows are a useful parameterized family, the power-of-Welch window family is similarly useful.
[src:dsp/window-function] Powers of the Welch or parabolic window are also symmetric beta distributions, and are purely algebraic functions (if the powers are rational), as opposed to most windows that are transcendental functions.
[src:dsp/window-function] If different exponents are used on the two factors in the Welch polynomial, the result is a general beta distribution, which is useful for making asymmetric window functions.
[src:dsp/window-function] Windows in the form of a cosine function offset by a constant, such as the popular Hamming and Hann windows, are sometimes called raised-cosine windows.
[src:dsp/window-function] The Hann window is particularly like the raised cosine distribution, which goes smoothly to zero at its ends.
[src:dsp/window-function] named after Julius von Hann, and sometimes referred to as *Hanning*, which derived from the verb "to Hann".
[src:dsp/window-function] It is also known as the **raised cosine**, because of its similarity to a raised-cosine distribution.
[src:dsp/window-function] This function is a member of both the cosine-sum and power-of-sine families.
[src:dsp/window-function] Unlike the Hamming window, the end points of the Hann window just touch zero.
[src:dsp/window-function] The resulting side-lobes roll off at about 18 dB per octave.
[src:dsp/window-function] Setting $a_{0}$ to approximately 0.54, or more precisely 25/46, produces the **Hamming window**, proposed by Richard W.
[src:dsp/window-function] This choice places a zero crossing at frequency 5π/(*N* − 1), which cancels the first sidelobe of the Hann window, giving it a height of about one-fifth that of the Hann window.
[src:dsp/window-function] The Hamming window is often called the **Hamming blip** when used for pulse shaping.
[src:dsp/window-function] Approximation of the coefficients to two decimal places substantially lowers the level of sidelobes, to a nearly equiripple condition.
[src:dsp/window-function] In the equiripple sense, the optimal values for the coefficients are *a*0 = 0.53836 and *a*1 = 0.46164.
[src:dsp/window-function] This family, which generalizes the raised-cosine windows, is also known as generalized cosine windows.
[src:dsp/window-function] In most cases, including the examples below, all coefficients *a**k* ≥ 0.
[src:dsp/window-function] These windows have only 2*K* + 1 non-zero *N*-point DFT coefficients.
[src:dsp/window-function] These exact values place zeros at the third and fourth sidelobes, but result in a discontinuity at the edges and a 6 dB/oct fall-off.
[src:dsp/window-function] The truncated coefficients do not null the sidelobes as well, but have an improved 18 dB/oct fall-off.
[src:dsp/window-function] The continuous form of the Nuttall window, $w_{0}(x),$ and its first derivative are continuous everywhere, like the Hann function.
[src:dsp/window-function] That is, the function goes to 0 at *x* = ±*N*/2, unlike the Blackman–Nuttall, Blackman–Harris, and Hamming windows.
[src:dsp/window-function] The Blackman window (*α* = 0.16) is also continuous with continuous derivative at the edge, but the "exact Blackman window" is not.
[src:dsp/window-function] A flat top window is a partially negative-valued window that has minimal scalloping loss in the frequency domain.
[src:dsp/window-function] That property is desirable for the measurement of amplitudes of sinusoidal frequency components.
[src:dsp/window-function] However, its broad bandwidth results in high noise bandwidth and wider frequency selection, which depending on the application could be a drawback.
[src:dsp/window-function] Other variations are available, such as sidelobes that roll off at the cost of higher values near the main lobe.
[src:dsp/window-function] Rife–Vincent windows are customarily scaled for unity average value, instead of unity peak value.
[src:dsp/window-function] The coefficient values below, applied to **Eq.1**, reflect that custom.
[src:dsp/window-function] Class I, Order 1 (*K* = 1): $a_{0}=1;\quad a_{1}=1$ Functionally equivalent to the Hann window and power of sine (*α* = 2).
[src:dsp/window-function] Class I is defined by minimizing the high-order sidelobe amplitude.
[src:dsp/window-function] Coefficients for orders up to K=4 are tabulated.
[src:dsp/window-function] Class II minimizes the main-lobe width for a given maximum side-lobe.
[src:dsp/window-function] Class III is a compromise for which order *K* = 2 resembles the § Blackman window.
[src:dsp/window-function] The corresponding $w_{0}(n)\,$ function is a cosine without the π/2 phase offset.
[src:dsp/window-function] So the *sine window* is sometimes also called *cosine window*.
[src:dsp/window-function] As it represents half a cycle of a sinusoidal function, it is also known variably as *half-sine window* or *half-cosine window*.
[src:dsp/window-function] The autocorrelation of a sine window produces a function known as the Bohman window.
[src:dsp/window-function] The rectangular window (*α* = 0), the sine window (*α* = 1), and the Hann window (*α* = 2) are members of this family.
[src:dsp/window-function] The Fourier transform of a Gaussian is also a Gaussian.
[src:dsp/window-function] Since the support of a Gaussian function extends to infinity, it must either be truncated at the ends of the window, or itself windowed with another zero-ended window.
[src:dsp/window-function] Since the log of a Gaussian produces a parabola, this can be used for nearly exact quadratic interpolation in frequency estimation.
[src:dsp/window-function] The standard deviation of the Gaussian function is *σ* · *N*/2 sampling periods.
[src:dsp/window-function] The confined Gaussian window yields the smallest possible root mean square frequency width *σ**ω* for a given temporal width (*N* + 1) *σ**t*.
[src:dsp/window-function] These windows optimize the RMS time-frequency bandwidth products.
[src:dsp/window-function] They are computed as the minimum eigenvectors of a parameter-dependent matrix.
[src:dsp/window-function] The confined Gaussian window family contains the § Sine window and the § Gaussian window in the limiting cases of large and small *σ**t*, respectively.
[src:dsp/window-function] The standard deviation of the approximate window is asymptotically equal (i.e. large values of *N*) to *L* × *σ**t* for *σt* < 0.14.
[src:dsp/window-function] A more generalized version of the Gaussian window is the generalized normal window.
[src:dsp/window-function] At $p=2$ , this is a Gaussian window and as p approaches $\infty$ , this approximates to a rectangular window.
[src:dsp/window-function] The Fourier transform of this window does not exist in a closed form for a general p .
[src:dsp/window-function] However, it demonstrates the other benefits of being smooth, adjustable bandwidth.
[src:dsp/window-function] Like the § Tukey window, this window naturally offers a "flat top" to control the amplitude attenuation of a time-series (on which we don't have a control with Gaussian window).
[src:dsp/window-function] In essence, it offers a good (controllable) compromise, in terms of spectral leakage, frequency resolution and amplitude attenuation, between the Gaussian window and the rectangular window.
[src:dsp/window-function] See also for a study on time-frequency representation of this window (or function).
[src:dsp/window-function] The Tukey window, also known as the *cosine-tapered window*, can be regarded as a cosine lobe of width *Nα*/2 (spanning *Nα*/2 + 1 observations) that is convolved with a rectangular window of width *N*(1 − *α*/2).
[src:dsp/window-function] At *α* = 0 it becomes rectangular, and at *α* = 1 it becomes a Hann window.
[src:dsp/window-function] The so-called "Planck-taper" window is a bump function that has been widely used in the theory of partitions of unity in manifolds.
[src:dsp/window-function] It is smooth (a $C^{\infty }$ function) everywhere, but is exactly zero outside of a compact region, exactly one over an interval within that region, and varies smoothly and monotonically between those limits.
[src:dsp/window-function] Its use as a window function in signal processing was first suggested in the context of gravitational-wave astronomy, inspired by the Planck distribution.
[src:dsp/window-function] The amount of tapering is controlled by the parameter *ε*, with smaller values giving sharper transitions.
[src:dsp/window-function] The DPSS (discrete prolate spheroidal sequence) or Slepian function, taper, or window maximizes the energy concentration in the main lobe, and is used in multitaper spectral analysis, which averages out noise in the spectrum and reduces information loss at the edges of the window.
[src:dsp/window-function] The main lobe ends at a frequency bin given by the parameter *α*.
[src:dsp/window-function] The Kaiser, or Kaiser–Bessel, window is a simple approximation of the DPSS window using Bessel functions, discovered by James Kaiser.
[src:dsp/window-function] where $I_{0}$ is the 0th-order modified Bessel function of the first kind.
[src:dsp/window-function] Variable parameter $\alpha$ determines the tradeoff between main lobe width and side lobe levels of the spectral leakage pattern.
[src:dsp/window-function] The main lobe width, in between the nulls, is given by $2{\sqrt {1+\alpha ^{2}}},$ in units of DFT bins, and a typical value of $\alpha$ is 3.
[src:dsp/window-function] Minimizes the Chebyshev norm of the side-lobes for a given main lobe width.
[src:dsp/window-function] is the unique positive real solution to $T_{N}(\beta )=10^{\alpha }$ , where the parameter *α* sets the Chebyshev norm of the sidelobes to −20*α* decibels.
[src:dsp/window-function] The Ultraspherical window was introduced in 1984 by Roy Streit and has application in antenna array design, non-recursive filter design, and spectrum analysis.
[src:dsp/window-function] Like other adjustable windows, the Ultraspherical window has parameters that can be used to control its Fourier transform main-lobe width and relative side-lobe amplitude.
[src:dsp/window-function] Uncommon to other windows, it has an additional parameter which can be used to set the rate at which side-lobes decrease (or increase) in amplitude.
[src:dsp/window-function] where $C_{N}^{\mu }$ is the Ultraspherical polynomial of degree N, and $x_{0}$ and $\mu$ control the side-lobe patterns.
[src:dsp/window-function] Certain specific values of $\mu$ yield other well-known windows: $\mu =0$ and $\mu =1$ give the Dolph–Chebyshev and Saramäki windows respectively.
[src:dsp/window-function] See here for illustration of Ultraspherical windows with varied parametrization.
[src:dsp/window-function] The Poisson window, or more generically the exponential window increases exponentially towards the center of the window and decreases exponentially in the second half.
[src:dsp/window-function] Since the exponential function never reaches zero, the values of the window at its limits are non-zero (it can be seen as the multiplication of an exponential function by a rectangular window ).
[src:dsp/window-function] where *τ* is the time constant of the function.
[src:dsp/window-function] The exponential function decays as *e* ≃ 2.71828 or approximately 8.69 dB per time constant.
[src:dsp/window-function] Window functions have also been constructed as multiplicative or additive combinations of other windows.
[src:dsp/window-function] A § Planck-taper window multiplied by a Kaiser window which is defined in terms of a modified Bessel function.
[src:dsp/window-function] This hybrid window function was introduced to decrease the peak side-lobe level of the Planck-taper window while still exploiting its good asymptotic decay.
[src:dsp/window-function] It has two tunable parameters, *ε* from the Planck-taper and *α* from the Kaiser window, so it can be adjusted to fit the requirements of a given signal.
[src:dsp/window-function] A Hann window multiplied by a Poisson window.
[src:dsp/window-function] For $\alpha \geqslant 2$ it has no side-lobes, as its Fourier transform drops off forever away from the main lobe without local minima.
[src:dsp/window-function] It can thus be used in hill climbing algorithms like Newton's method.
[src:dsp/window-function] where *α* is a parameter that controls the slope of the exponential.
[src:dsp/window-function] The GAP window is a family of adjustable window functions that are based on a symmetrical polynomial expansion of order K .
[src:dsp/window-function] It is continuous with continuous derivative everywhere.
